// MedMasters: Rheumatology - JCAT/FCPS Part 1 Medicine
// 250 MCQs - First Aid for USMLE Step 1 + Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine
(function(){
  if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
  window.MM['med_p2_rheuma'] = [
    {q:'Which of the following is the most common radiographic finding in osteoarthritis?',o:['Uniform joint space narrowing','Marginal erosions','Subchondral sclerosis','Symmetrical joint involvement'],a:2,e:`Osteoarthritis radiographic features include osteophytes (bone spurs), joint space narrowing, subchondral sclerosis and cysts; subchondral sclerosis appears as a dense bony plate beneath cartilage loss.<br><br>Mechanical wear and tear destroys articular cartilage, exposing subchondral bone which compacts and hardens. This reactive sclerosis is a hallmark plain-film feature alongside asymmetric joint space narrowing.<br><br>Marginal erosions characterise rheumatoid arthritis with juxtaarticular osteopenia, not OA; uniform joint space narrowing typifies inflammatory disease whereas OA is asymmetric; symmetric joint involvement also points away from OA.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Heberden’s nodes are clinical markers of osteoarthritis located at which joints?',o:['Distal interphalangeal joints','Carpometacarpal joints','Metacarpophalangeal joints','Proximal interphalangeal joints'],a:0,e:`Heberden nodes are classical bony swellings located at the distal interphalangeal joints, reflecting marginal osteophyte formation in primary nodal osteoarthritis of the hands.<br><br>Osteoarthritis involves DIP (Heberden nodes) and PIP (Bouchard nodes), and 1st CMC; the metacarpophalangeal joints are characteristically spared, distinguishing OA from rheumatoid arthritis on physical examination.<br><br>Carpometacarpal involvement gives thumb-base osteoarthritis but does not produce nodal swellings; metacarpophalangeal joints are spared in primary OA; PIP swellings are termed Bouchard nodes, not Heberden.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the primary characteristic of morning stiffness in a patient with osteoarthritis?',o:['Occurs only in the evening','Lasts more than 1 hour','Lasts less than 30 minutes','Improves with rest'],a:2,e:`Morning stiffness in osteoarthritis lasts less than 30 minutes and resolves quickly with movement, reflecting non-inflammatory mechanical pain rather than active synovitis.<br><br>Pain in OA occurs in weight-bearing joints after use, typically worsening at the end of the day and improving with rest. Systemic features are absent, contrasting sharply with rheumatoid disease.<br><br>Stiffness lasting more than one hour suggests rheumatoid arthritis with synovial inflammation; pain improving with rest fits OA but is not stiffness duration; evening-only stiffness is not a recognised pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is considered the strongest risk factor for the development of osteoarthritis of the knee?',o:['Male gender','Obesity','Vitamin D deficiency','Low calcium intake'],a:1,e:`Obesity is the strongest modifiable risk factor for knee osteoarthritis, increasing mechanical load across the medial tibiofemoral compartment and accelerating cartilage breakdown.<br><br>OA predisposing factors include age, female sex, obesity, and joint trauma. Weight loss has substantial benefit on symptoms when the patient is obese and is one of the most effective treatments available.<br><br>Male gender is not a knee OA risk factor; vitamin D deficiency contributes to osteomalacia and rickets rather than OA; low calcium intake affects bone mineralisation but is not implicated in cartilage degeneration.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which joints are most commonly spared in primary osteoarthritis?',o:['Metacarpophalangeal joints','Lumbar spine','Distal interphalangeal joints','Hips and knees'],a:0,e:`Metacarpophalangeal joints are characteristically spared in primary osteoarthritis; involvement of MCPs should raise suspicion for rheumatoid arthritis or secondary OA from haemochromatosis.<br><br>OA classically involves the DIP joints (Heberden nodes), PIP joints (Bouchard nodes), and 1st carpometacarpal joint of the thumb. Rheumatoid arthritis involves MCP, PIP, and wrist; not DIP or 1st CMC.<br><br>Lumbar spine is commonly affected by spondylotic OA; DIP joints are the most typical site of nodal OA, the opposite of spared; hips and knees are major weight-bearing OA targets.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the pathological hallmark of osteoarthritis?',o:['Purulent joint effusion','Synovial hypertrophy','Pannus formation','Loss of articular cartilage'],a:3,e:`Loss of articular cartilage is the pathological hallmark of osteoarthritis; chondrocytes mediate progressive degradation with inadequate repair, exposing subchondral bone.<br><br>Mechanical wear and tear destroys articular cartilage in this degenerative joint disease. Type II collagen and aggrecan content fall, fissuring of the cartilage surface (fibrillation) follows, and load-bearing injury results.<br><br>Purulent effusion characterises septic arthritis with WBC over 50,000; synovial hypertrophy and pannus formation define rheumatoid arthritis where inflammatory cytokines erode cartilage and bone, not OA.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Crepitus felt during physical examination of an osteoarthritic joint is caused by:',o:['Accumulation of uric acid crystals','Irregular joint surfaces rubbing together','Gas bubbles bursting in synovial fluid','Stretching of inflamed ligaments'],a:1,e:`Crepitus in osteoarthritis arises from irregular, denuded joint surfaces grinding against one another, producing the palpable and audible grating felt on joint movement.<br><br>As articular cartilage thins and fissures, exposed subchondral bone becomes polished (eburnation). The roughened surfaces contact during motion, generating coarse crepitus characteristic of advanced osteoarthritic joints.<br><br>Uric acid crystal accumulation defines gout, not OA crepitus; gas bubbles bursting in synovial fluid produce harmless cracking, not pathological crepitus; ligament inflammation does not generate joint-surface grating.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which pharmacological agent is often recommended as a first-line topical treatment for localized knee osteoarthritis?',o:['Hydroxychloroquine','Prednisone','Diclofenac gel','Methotrexate'],a:2,e:`Topical diclofenac gel is recommended as a first-line topical treatment for localised knee osteoarthritis, providing analgesia with minimal systemic absorption and lower gastrointestinal risk than oral NSAIDs.<br><br>Davidson's notes paracetamol and topical NSAIDs are safe in older people, with no important drug interactions or contraindications. Topical NSAIDs are particularly helpful for knee and hand OA when paracetamol is insufficient.<br><br>Methotrexate and hydroxychloroquine are disease-modifying agents used in rheumatoid arthritis, not OA; oral prednisone is reserved for inflammatory disease and is not first-line topical therapy for OA.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'In the Kellgren-Lawrence grading system for osteoarthritis, Grade 4 is characterized by:',o:['Large osteophytes and marked joint space narrowing','Doubtful narrowing of joint space','Normal joint appearance','Minimal osteophytes'],a:0,e:`Kellgren-Lawrence Grade 4 osteoarthritis represents end-stage disease characterised by large osteophytes, marked joint space narrowing, severe subchondral sclerosis, and definite bony deformity.<br><br>The grading scale runs from Grade 0 (normal) through doubtful narrowing, definite osteophytes, multiple osteophytes with definite narrowing, to Grade 4 with severe structural change. Higher grades correlate with surgical referral.<br><br>Doubtful joint space narrowing reflects Grade 1 disease; minimal osteophytes describe Grade 2 changes; a normal joint appearance corresponds to Grade 0, none of these matching the severe end-stage findings of Grade 4.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Secondary osteoarthritis can be caused by which of the following metabolic conditions?',o:['Iron deficiency anemia','Hyponatremia','Hypothyroidism','Hemochromatosis'],a:3,e:`Haemochromatosis causes secondary osteoarthritis through iron deposition in articular cartilage, classically affecting the second and third metacarpophalangeal joints, an unusual site for primary OA.<br><br>Secondary OA arises from prior joint damage or metabolic disease; haemochromatosis, Wilson disease, acromegaly, and ochronosis all predispose. Calcium pyrophosphate crystal deposition often coexists, accelerating cartilage breakdown in these patients.<br><br>Hypothyroidism is not a recognised cause of secondary OA; iron deficiency anaemia and hyponatraemia are unrelated electrolyte and haematologic disorders without any direct link to articular cartilage degeneration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the main structural component of articular cartilage that degrades in osteoarthritis?',o:['Keratin','Type I collagen','Type II collagen','Elastin fibers'],a:2,e:`Type II collagen is the main structural collagen of articular cartilage; in osteoarthritis, accelerated degradation of type II collagen and aggrecan undermines the matrix and produces fibrillation.<br><br>Cartilage matrix concentration of aggrecan falls and the tissue becomes vulnerable to load-bearing injury. Fissuring of the cartilage surface follows, leading to progressive cartilage thinning and loss with disease progression.<br><br>Type I collagen predominates in bone, tendon, and skin, not articular cartilage; elastin fibres provide elasticity to skin and large arteries; keratin is the principal structural protein of epidermis and hair.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Bouchard’s nodes are found at which of the following locations?',o:['PIP joints','DIP joints','Wrist','MCP joints'],a:0,e:`Bouchard nodes are bony swellings of the proximal interphalangeal joints reflecting marginal osteophyte formation, occurring alongside Heberden nodes in nodal generalised osteoarthritis of the hands.<br><br>OA involves DIP (Heberden nodes), PIP (Bouchard nodes), and the 1st CMC joint; not the MCPs. Patients have bilateral, symmetrical involvement with marked female preponderance and peak onset in middle age.<br><br>DIP joint swellings are Heberden nodes, not Bouchard; wrist involvement points to rheumatoid arthritis, not osteoarthritis; metacarpophalangeal joints are spared in primary OA, ruling out that location.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a non-pharmacological "cornerstone" of osteoarthritis management?',o:['Heavy weightlifting','Complete bed rest','High-impact running','Weight loss and exercise'],a:3,e:`Weight loss and exercise are the cornerstones of non-pharmacological osteoarthritis management; they improve symptoms, increase functional capacity, and reduce mechanical load across affected weight-bearing joints.<br><br>Weight loss has substantial beneficial effect on symptoms if the patient is obese. Local muscle strengthening exercises around the affected joint reduce pain, while aerobic exercise improves balance and reduces falls.<br><br>Heavy weightlifting accelerates cartilage damage; complete bed rest leads to muscle wasting and worsens function; high-impact running stresses already compromised joints, making it inappropriate as initial OA management.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Osteophyte formation is a compensatory response to:',o:['Systemic inflammation','Joint instability and cartilage loss','Bacterial infection','Increased synovial fluid production'],a:1,e:`Osteophytes form as a compensatory bony response to joint instability and cartilage loss; they represent attempts to redistribute load and stabilise the joint by expanding the articular surface area.<br><br>Joint findings in osteoarthritis include osteophytes (bone spurs), joint space narrowing, subchondral sclerosis and cysts. These changes evolve over years and produce the deformity characteristic of advanced disease.<br><br>Systemic inflammation drives rheumatoid pannus, not OA osteophytes; bacterial infection causes septic arthritis; increased synovial fluid production reflects effusion in inflammatory or post-traumatic states, not bony spur formation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Unlike rheumatoid arthritis, osteoarthritis is generally considered:',o:['A non-inflammatory, "wear and tear" disease','A systemic inflammatory disease','An autoimmune disease','A genetic deficiency of collagen'],a:0,e:`Osteoarthritis is generally considered a non-inflammatory, wear and tear disease; pathogenesis is mechanical destruction of articular cartilage with inadequate chondrocyte repair, distinct from autoimmune synovitis.<br><br>OA pathogenesis contrasts with rheumatoid arthritis where autoimmune inflammatory cytokines and cells induce pannus formation that erodes articular cartilage and bone. Synovial fluid in OA shows WBC less than 2000 per mm3.<br><br>OA is not autoimmune; it lacks systemic inflammatory features such as fever, elevated CRP, or weight loss; it is not a primary genetic collagen deficiency though heritable factors influence risk.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which imaging modality is most cost-effective for the initial diagnosis of osteoarthritis?',o:['Ultrasound','CT scan','Plain Radiography','MRI'],a:2,e:`Plain radiography is the most cost-effective initial imaging modality for osteoarthritis, demonstrating osteophytes, joint space narrowing, subchondral sclerosis, and cysts with high specificity.<br><br>Standing anteroposterior knee X-rays assess tibiofemoral cartilage loss; non-weight-bearing pelvis views adequately evaluate hip OA. Plain films are inexpensive, widely available, and grade severity using Kellgren-Lawrence classification.<br><br>MRI better visualises soft tissue and early cartilage changes but is expensive; CT provides bony detail at higher radiation dose; ultrasound has limited role beyond assessing effusion or guiding intra-articular injection.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Synovial fluid analysis in osteoarthritis typically shows:',o:['Presence of rhomboid crystals','>50,000 WBC/mm³','Positive Gram stain','<2,000 WBC/mm³ (non-inflammatory)'],a:3,e:`Synovial fluid in osteoarthritis is non-inflammatory with WBC less than 2000 per mm3, clear or straw-coloured, with normal viscosity reflecting the mechanical rather than autoimmune nature of disease.<br><br>Aspiration of an OA joint helps exclude crystal disease and infection. Inflammatory fluid (rheumatoid arthritis) shows WBC over 2000, while septic fluid is purulent with WBC over 50,000 per mm3.<br><br>WBC over 50,000 indicates septic arthritis; rhomboid crystals weakly positively birefringent characterise calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease; positive Gram stain confirms bacterial joint infection, none of which feature in OA.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the goal of viscosupplementation in treating osteoarthritis?',o:['To kill bacteria in the joint','To supplement hyaluronic acid in synovial fluid','To numb the nerves permanently','To replace lost bone'],a:1,e:`Viscosupplementation involves intra-articular injection of hyaluronic acid to supplement the natural lubricating component of synovial fluid, aiming to restore joint cushioning and reduce mechanical pain in OA.<br><br>Intra-articular injections of hyaluronic acid can help to an extent in knee OA, but the treatment is expensive and the effect short-lived. The UK has not considered them cost-effective alternatives to standard care.<br><br>Hyaluronic acid injections do not replace bone, kill bacteria (the joint is not infected in OA), or numb nerves permanently; nerve ablation is a different modality used in selected refractory pain cases.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Genu varum (bow-leggedness) is commonly associated with osteoarthritis of which knee compartment?',o:['Lateral compartment','Posterior compartment','Patellofemoral compartment','Medial compartment'],a:3,e:`Genu varum (bow-leggedness) reflects medial compartment knee osteoarthritis where preferential cartilage loss begins medially, narrowing the joint space and shifting the mechanical axis inward.<br><br>Knee cartilage loss begins medially in OA, producing the characteristic bowlegged deformity. Asymmetric cartilage thinning concentrates load on the medial tibial plateau, accelerating further degenerative change in that compartment.<br><br>Lateral compartment OA produces valgus (knock-knee) deformity, the opposite alignment; posterior compartment is not a recognised tibiofemoral subdivision; patellofemoral OA causes anterior knee pain without varus angulation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following increases the risk of hip osteoarthritis?',o:['Developmental dysplasia of the hip','Routine swimming','Excessive vitamin C intake','Female gender under age 30'],a:0,e:`Developmental dysplasia of the hip predisposes to early secondary osteoarthritis through abnormal load distribution across an incongruent joint, producing accelerated cartilage wear from young adulthood onward.<br><br>Developmental abnormalities such as developmental dysplasia of the hip are associated with a high risk of OA, presumably due to abnormal load distribution. Limb deformity from Paget disease similarly increases hip OA risk.<br><br>Routine swimming is low-impact and protective; excessive vitamin C intake has no established link to OA; female gender under thirty is not a major risk demographic since primary hip OA peaks in older adults.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Eburnation in osteoarthritis refers to:',o:['Excessive synovial swelling','Formation of new cartilage','Polished, ivory-like appearance of exposed subchondral bone','Softening of the bone marrow'],a:2,e:`Eburnation describes the polished, ivory-like appearance of exposed subchondral bone where overlying cartilage has been completely lost; the surface becomes hard, smooth, and dense from continuous mechanical contact.<br><br>Once cartilage erodes through, opposing bone surfaces grind against each other. The subchondral bone responds with sclerosis and surface polishing, producing eburnation visible at arthroscopy and contributing to joint stiffness.<br><br>Formation of new cartilage does not occur in OA; excessive synovial swelling describes effusion in inflammatory arthritis; softening of bone marrow characterises osteomyelitis or marrow oedema, none of which define eburnation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the primary symptom that leads patients with osteoarthritis to seek medical care?',o:['Fever','Joint pain','Weight loss','Skin rash'],a:1,e:`Joint pain is the primary symptom that drives patients with osteoarthritis to seek medical care; pain typically worsens with use, improves with rest, and progresses gradually over years.<br><br>Pain in weight-bearing joints after use, often at the end of the day, dominates the clinical picture. As disease advances, pain becomes constant and disturbs sleep, prompting consultation and consideration of joint replacement.<br><br>Fever indicates infection or inflammatory arthritis; skin rash points to connective tissue disease such as lupus or psoriatic arthritis; weight loss is a systemic feature absent in osteoarthritis since OA causes no constitutional symptoms.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug class should be used with caution in elderly OA patients due to GI and renal risks?',o:['Vitamin D','Acetaminophen','Glucosamine','NSAIDs'],a:3,e:`NSAIDs require caution in elderly osteoarthritis patients because of substantial gastrointestinal bleeding risk and renal impairment, particularly with concurrent ACE inhibitor or diuretic use.<br><br>Oral NSAIDs are significantly more effective than paracetamol but carry adverse effects including peptic ulceration, hypertension, fluid retention, and reduced renal function. Selective COX-2 inhibitors reduce gastrointestinal but not cardiovascular risk.<br><br>Acetaminophen has favourable safety in elderly when dose-adjusted; glucosamine is a nutraceutical of questionable efficacy without major toxicity; vitamin D supports bone health and is generally safe at recommended doses.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Joint "locking" or "giving way" in an osteoarthritic knee often suggests:',o:['Internal derangement or loose bodies','Systemic lupus','Muscle wasting only','Nerve entrapment'],a:0,e:`Locking or giving way of an osteoarthritic knee suggests internal derangement or loose bodies, fragments of detached cartilage or bone interfering with smooth articulation.<br><br>Cartilage fragments break off advanced OA joints and float in the synovial cavity. They wedge between articulating surfaces causing sudden mechanical block (locking), and unstable joints buckle under weight (giving way).<br><br>Systemic lupus produces inflammatory arthritis without mechanical locking; muscle wasting alone does not cause locking, though it contributes to instability; nerve entrapment causes paraesthesiae and weakness rather than mechanical block.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The "gel phenomenon" in osteoarthritis refers to:',o:['The feeling of fluid moving in the joint','Stiffness after periods of inactivity','The consistency of synovial fluid in gout','The use of topical gels for pain'],a:1,e:`The gel phenomenon describes joint stiffness that develops after periods of inactivity (such as sitting) and resolves within minutes of resumed movement, classically seen in osteoarthritis.<br><br>Unlike inflammatory morning stiffness lasting more than one hour, OA gelling lasts less than 30 minutes and reflects mechanical viscoelastic properties of degenerated cartilage and synovium settling at rest, then loosening with motion.<br><br>Topical pain gels are pharmacological agents, not phenomena; gout synovial fluid contains needle-shaped urate crystals; the sensation of fluid moving describes effusion or ballottement, not the stiffness of gelling.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a risk factor for generalized nodal osteoarthritis?',o:['Low protein diet','History of fractures','Family history','Smoking'],a:2,e:`Family history is a recognised risk factor for generalised nodal osteoarthritis, with a strong genetic predisposition particularly in postmenopausal women developing Heberden and Bouchard nodes.<br><br>Nodal OA shows marked female preponderance with peak onset in middle age. Daughters of women with nodal OA themselves have increased risk. Genetic factors influence cartilage matrix protein structure and joint shape.<br><br>Smoking shows a paradoxical inverse association with OA in some studies but is not a risk factor; low protein diet does not predispose; previous fractures cause local secondary OA rather than generalised nodal disease.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'At what stage of osteoarthritis is total joint replacement usually indicated?',o:['At the first sign of pain','When conservative treatments fail and pain is refractory','When radiographic changes are mild','Only if the patient is under age 50'],a:1,e:`Total joint replacement in osteoarthritis is indicated when conservative treatments fail and pain becomes refractory, particularly when daily function and sleep are severely impaired by joint pain.<br><br>Davidson's describes total joint replacement as an excellent cost-effective treatment for severe disabling knee or hip OA in older people, with no upper age limit. Over 95% function well into the second decade.<br><br>Surgery at the first sign of pain is inappropriate when conservative measures remain untried; mild radiographic changes do not warrant arthroplasty; age under fifty is a relative contraindication, not a strict indication.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is NOT a typical radiographic feature of osteoarthritis?',o:['Subchondral cysts','Osteophytes','Periarticular osteopenia','Asymmetric joint space narrowing'],a:2,e:`Periarticular osteopenia is a feature of rheumatoid arthritis caused by inflammatory cytokine-mediated bone resorption near inflamed joints, and is NOT typical of osteoarthritis.<br><br>OA radiographic features are osteophytes (bone spurs), joint space narrowing, subchondral sclerosis and cysts. Subchondral bone shows increased rather than decreased density, distinguishing OA from inflammatory or rheumatoid disease.<br><br>Osteophytes, subchondral cysts, and asymmetric joint space narrowing are all hallmark OA radiographic findings; only periarticular osteopenia is absent in OA, making it the correct exclusion in this question.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'"First-step" pain in the morning that improves after a few minutes of walking is classic for:',o:['Bone cancer','Fibromyalgia','Septic arthritis','Osteoarthritis'],a:3,e:`First-step pain in the morning that improves after a few minutes of walking is classic for osteoarthritis, reflecting mechanical stiffness that loosens rapidly with joint motion.<br><br>Pain in weight-bearing joints after use, improving with rest, alongside short-lived gelling stiffness, characterises OA. The first steps of the day are typically painful, then ease as cartilage and synovium mobilise.<br><br>Bone cancer pain is unrelenting and worse at night; fibromyalgia produces widespread non-articular tenderness without first-step pattern; septic arthritis presents with hot, swollen joint and fever rather than mechanical stiffness.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which cellular component is responsible for the balance of cartilage synthesis and degradation?',o:['Chondrocytes','Fibroblasts','Osteoblasts','Osteoclasts'],a:0,e:`Chondrocytes are the resident cells of articular cartilage responsible for the dynamic balance between matrix synthesis and degradation; their dysfunction underlies osteoarthritis progression.<br><br>In OA, chondrocytes mediate degradation and inadequate repair. Synthesis of aggrecan and type II collagen continues at increased rate, but accelerated degradation of major structural cartilage components ultimately predominates.<br><br>Osteoblasts form bone matrix and osteoclasts resorb it; both are bone, not cartilage cells. Fibroblasts populate connective tissue, ligaments, and tendons rather than synthesising the unique aggrecan-rich cartilage matrix.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Erosive osteoarthritis is a specific subset that most commonly affects:',o:['The knees','The small joints of the hands','The cervical spine','The hips'],a:1,e:`Erosive osteoarthritis is a specific aggressive subset that most commonly affects the small joints of the hands, particularly the DIP and PIP joints, with central erosions on radiography.<br><br>Affected hand joints show inflammatory features superimposed on classic OA, including swelling and tenderness with central erosions producing gull-wing deformity. Postmenopausal women are most commonly affected, with overlap to nodal OA.<br><br>Knee OA is common but not the typical site of erosive subtype; cervical spine spondylosis affects facet joints differently; hip OA produces classic mechanical features without the central erosive pattern of hand involvement.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The presence of a "Baker’s cyst" is often associated with osteoarthritis of the:',o:['Knee','Shoulder','Hip','Ankle'],a:0,e:`Baker's cyst is a popliteal fossa swelling representing posterior herniation of synovial fluid through the knee capsule, frequently associated with knee osteoarthritis and effusion.<br><br>Increased intra-articular pressure from chronic effusion drives synovial fluid into the gastrocnemius-semimembranosus bursa. Rupture causes acute calf pain mimicking deep vein thrombosis; ultrasound distinguishes the two clinical scenarios.<br><br>Hip OA produces groin pain rather than popliteal swelling; shoulder OA causes anterior or lateral pain without bursal cysts in the popliteal region; ankle OA produces malleolar swelling, not Baker's cysts.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following describes the pain of hip osteoarthritis?',o:['Pain at the lower back radiating to the foot','Pain in the lateral buttock only','Pain only during sleep','Pain in the groin radiating to the knee'],a:3,e:`Hip osteoarthritis classically presents with pain in the groin radiating to the knee via the obturator nerve, often misleading clinicians toward primary knee pathology.<br><br>Pain is felt in the groin and may radiate down the medial thigh to the knee. Restricted internal rotation with the hip flexed is the earliest and most sensitive sign; flexion deformity develops later.<br><br>Lateral buttock-only pain suggests trochanteric bursitis or sciatica; lower back radiating to foot is sciatica from lumbar pathology; pain only during sleep without movement-related component is atypical for mechanical hip OA.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Intra-articular corticosteroid injections provide:',o:['Permanent cure for OA','Improvement in bone density','Short-term symptomatic relief of inflammation','Regeneration of cartilage'],a:2,e:`Intra-articular corticosteroid injections provide short-term symptomatic relief of inflammation in osteoarthritic joints, particularly useful for tiding patients over a special event or pre-surgical optimisation.<br><br>Intra-articular injection of glucocorticoid is a very safe and often effective treatment, particularly useful for tiding a patient over a special event. Effect typically lasts weeks to a few months without disease modification.<br><br>Steroids cannot permanently cure OA; cartilage regeneration does not occur with intra-articular injections and remains an unmet therapeutic goal; bone density improvement requires bisphosphonates or denosumab, not local steroid.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which factor contributes to the "grating" sensation (crepitus) in OA?',o:['Loss of smooth articular cartilage','Excessive lubrication','Tendonitis','Ligament laxity'],a:0,e:`Loss of smooth articular cartilage exposes irregular subchondral bone surfaces, producing the grating sensation of crepitus when one denuded surface contacts the opposing damaged surface during motion.<br><br>As OA progresses, fibrillation gives way to full-thickness cartilage loss, leaving polished sclerotic bone (eburnation) in contact. The mechanical irregularity translates into palpable and audible crepitus on examination.<br><br>Excessive lubrication would reduce friction and crepitus; ligament laxity causes instability rather than grating; tendonitis produces tendon-localised pain and tenderness without intra-articular crepitus on joint movement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Osteoarthritis of the first carpometacarpal joint affects:',o:['The tip of the index finger','The wrist bone (ulna)','The base of the thumb','The middle of the palm'],a:2,e:`First carpometacarpal joint osteoarthritis affects the base of the thumb and produces pain on pinch and grip; the squared appearance reflects subluxation and adductor contracture.<br><br>OA characteristically involves DIP, PIP, and 1st CMC joints. Thumb-base OA limits opposition and key pinch, with tenderness over the trapeziometacarpal joint; splinting and intra-articular injection often help symptomatically.<br><br>The index fingertip is a DIP location, not a thumb base; the ulna is a forearm bone, not a thumb articulation; the middle palm contains tendons and intrinsic muscles without major articular surfaces affected by primary OA.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the effect of physical therapy in OA management?',o:['It serves no purpose once cartilage is gone','It strengthens supporting muscles to reduce joint load','It is only used for post-surgical recovery','It increases joint friction'],a:1,e:`Physical therapy in osteoarthritis strengthens supporting muscles around the affected joint, reducing mechanical load transmitted across damaged articular surfaces and improving functional capacity.<br><br>Local muscle strengthening exercises reduce pain. Aerobic exercise improves balance and reduces tendency to fall. These benefits accrue regardless of radiographic severity and form part of every OA management plan from diagnosis onward.<br><br>Physical therapy reduces, not increases, joint friction by stabilising musculature; cartilage loss does not abolish therapy benefit since muscle support remains valuable; therapy is used pre-operatively and conservatively, not solely post-surgical.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following differentiates OA from Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA)?',o:['OA affects the MCP joints primarily','RA is usually asymmetrical; OA is symmetrical','OA has positive Rheumatoid Factor','OA lacks systemic symptoms like fever and malaise'],a:3,e:`Osteoarthritis lacks systemic symptoms such as fever, fatigue, or weight loss, distinguishing it from rheumatoid arthritis where extraarticular inflammatory features are common.<br><br>OA presentation is mechanical: pain in weight-bearing joints after use, improving with rest, asymmetric, with morning stiffness under thirty minutes. Rheumatoid arthritis shows symmetric polyarthritis, prolonged morning stiffness, and constitutional symptoms.<br><br>OA does not have positive rheumatoid factor (RF is anti-IgG, found in 80% of RA patients); RA is symmetric, OA asymmetric (the choices reverse this); MCP joints are RA-typical, while OA spares MCPs.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Subchondral cysts in OA are formed by:',o:['Bacterial invasion','Tumor growth','Pressure of synovial fluid forced through cartilage defects','Excessive calcium deposits'],a:2,e:`Subchondral cysts in osteoarthritis form when synovial fluid is forced through cartilage defects under high intra-articular pressure during weight-bearing, dissecting into the underlying bone.<br><br>Joint findings in OA include osteophytes, joint space narrowing, subchondral sclerosis and cysts. The cysts are also called geodes and appear as well-circumscribed lucencies adjacent to areas of cartilage loss on plain films.<br><br>Bacterial invasion produces septic osteomyelitic cavities; tumours produce expansile lytic lesions with cortical destruction; excessive calcium deposits cause chondrocalcinosis and crystal arthropathy rather than fluid-filled subchondral cysts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Malalignment of the joint in OA is often a result of:',o:['Asymmetric cartilage loss and remodeling','Uniform cartilage loss','Overuse of the opposite limb','Vitamin deficiency'],a:0,e:`Joint malalignment in osteoarthritis arises from asymmetric cartilage loss and bony remodelling; uneven thinning shifts the mechanical axis and produces angular deformities such as varus or valgus.<br><br>Knee cartilage loss begins medially, producing bowlegged (varus) deformity. Continued asymmetric load drives progressive remodelling with osteophytes, subchondral sclerosis, and worsening alignment, creating a self-perpetuating cycle of degeneration.<br><br>Uniform cartilage loss would preserve alignment, the opposite of malalignment; overuse of the opposite limb causes contralateral but not malaligned OA; vitamin deficiency causes osteomalacia or rickets, not joint angulation from cartilage loss.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which inflammatory mediator is often found in low levels in OA synovial fluid?',o:['Hemoglobin','Interleukin-1 (IL-1)','Growth hormone','Insulin'],a:1,e:`Interleukin-1 (IL-1) is found in lower levels in osteoarthritic synovial fluid compared with rheumatoid arthritis, where IL-1 and TNF-alpha drive aggressive synovitis and cartilage erosion.<br><br>OA synovial fluid is non-inflammatory with WBC under 2000 per mm3 and modestly elevated cytokines. IL-1 still contributes to chondrocyte-mediated matrix degradation in OA but at concentrations far lower than RA.<br><br>Hemoglobin appears in haemarthrosis, not chronic OA effusion; insulin and growth hormone are systemic endocrine hormones without recognised roles in OA synovial fluid pathology or articular cartilage breakdown.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the most common site for spinal osteoarthritis?',o:['Thoracic spine','Sacrum','Upper cervical spine','Mid-cervical and lower lumbar regions'],a:3,e:`Spinal osteoarthritis most commonly affects the mid-cervical and lower lumbar regions, sites of greatest mobility and mechanical loading where facet joints and intervertebral discs degenerate together.<br><br>Cervical and lumbar segments bear the greatest range-of-motion stress over a lifetime, predisposing to cartilage thinning, osteophyte formation, and disc-space narrowing. Spondylosis at these levels causes pain and nerve root entrapment.<br><br>The thoracic spine is relatively immobile and stabilised by rib articulations; the upper cervical spine is uncommonly affected by primary OA; the sacrum is fused and not subject to mobile joint OA.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which movement is usually lost first in hip osteoarthritis?',o:['Flexion','Internal rotation','Extension','Adduction'],a:1,e:`Internal rotation is the earliest movement lost in hip osteoarthritis; restriction with the hip flexed is the most sensitive clinical sign, often preceding fixed flexion deformity.<br><br>Davidson's identifies pain and restriction of internal rotation with the hip flexed as the earliest and most sensitive sign of hip OA. Other movements may subsequently be restricted and painful as disease progresses.<br><br>Flexion is preserved early then lost late as fixed flexion deformity develops; extension limitation occurs late in disease; adduction restriction is non-specific and not the earliest detectable change.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Does smoking increase the risk of osteoarthritis?',o:['It only affects OA of the hands','It causes OA by increasing bone density','Yes, it is a primary cause','No, some studies suggest a strange inverse correlation, but it’s not protective'],a:3,e:`Smoking does not increase OA risk; some studies suggest a paradoxical inverse correlation, though smoking is not protective and remains harmful for cardiovascular and respiratory health.<br><br>The mechanism behind the inverse association is unclear and may reflect lower body weight in smokers or confounding. Regardless, smoking causes substantial harm and should never be recommended for any preventive purpose.<br><br>Smoking is not a primary cause of OA; hand-only OA effect is not specific to smoking; smoking does not increase bone density to cause OA, and bone density itself is not the OA mechanism.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The use of a cane in the contralateral hand helps OA by:',o:['Reducing the load on the affected hip or knee','Preventing hand OA','Improving eyesight','Increasing weight on the painful joint'],a:0,e:`A cane held in the contralateral hand reduces load on the affected hip or knee by transferring weight through the upper limb during stance phase.<br><br>Biomechanically, the cane creates an external moment counteracting body weight on the affected side, reducing joint reaction force by up to 25 percent. Proper technique should be taught for maximum benefit.<br><br>Holding the cane on the painful side increases load on the affected joint; canes do not prevent hand OA or improve eyesight; weight transfer is to the cane, not concentrated on the painful joint.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which metabolic disorder is associated with "Crowned Dens Syndrome" (a variation of OA/pseudogout)?',o:['Hypernatremia','Gout','CPPD (Calcium pyrophosphate deposition)','Diabetes Mellitus'],a:2,e:`Crowned dens syndrome is a manifestation of calcium pyrophosphate deposition (CPPD) disease at the atlanto-axial junction, where pyrophosphate crystals form a calcified halo around the odontoid peg.<br><br>CPPD deposition involves calcium pyrophosphate crystals within the joint space, occurring in patients over 50, both sexes equally. Idiopathic in most; sometimes associated with haemochromatosis, hyperparathyroidism, or joint trauma in older patients.<br><br>Hypernatraemia is an electrolyte disturbance unrelated to crystal deposition; gout deposits monosodium urate, not pyrophosphate; diabetes mellitus does not cause crowned dens syndrome through any recognised crystal-deposition mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The term "Wear and Tear" is becoming outdated because OA is now seen as:',o:['An active biological process involving the whole joint','A temporary muscle strain','A purely psychological condition','A contagious infection'],a:0,e:`Wear and tear is increasingly outdated because osteoarthritis is now recognised as an active biological process involving the entire joint, including cartilage, bone, synovium, and ligaments.<br><br>Chondrocytes mediate degradation and inadequate repair in a metabolically active disease. Subchondral bone remodels, synovium becomes mildly inflamed, and capsular structures contribute to pain. OA is therefore biologically dynamic, not mechanical.<br><br>OA is not psychological; it is not contagious as no infectious agent is involved; it is not a temporary muscle strain since structural cartilage and bone changes persist progressively over years.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a symptom of advanced OA of the spine?',o:['Excessive hair growth over the spine','Increased height','Improved flexibility','Spinal stenosis and nerve root compression'],a:3,e:`Advanced spinal osteoarthritis produces spinal stenosis and nerve root compression as osteophytes encroach on the central canal and neural foramina, causing radiculopathy and neurogenic claudication.<br><br>Lumbar spondylosis with osteophytes and ligamentum flavum hypertrophy narrows the spinal canal, producing pain, paraesthesiae, and weakness on walking that resolves with sitting or lumbar flexion. Decompressive surgery may be required for refractory cases.<br><br>OA reduces flexibility rather than improving it; vertebral collapse and disc-space loss reduce height rather than increasing it; abnormal hair growth is not a feature of degenerative spinal disease at any stage.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Patellofemoral osteoarthritis typically causes pain during:',o:['Lying flat','Sleeping','Climbing or descending stairs','Standing still'],a:2,e:`Patellofemoral osteoarthritis typically causes anterior knee pain during stair climbing or descent, when patellar reaction force against the trochlea is greatest under flexed-knee loading conditions.<br><br>Pain is also worse rising from a chair or squatting. Patellofemoral OA may occur in isolation or alongside tibiofemoral OA. Quadriceps strengthening, weight loss, and topical NSAIDs are mainstays of management.<br><br>Lying flat unloads the patellofemoral joint and is painless; sleep is unaffected since the joint is at rest; standing still produces minimal patellofemoral force compared with stair climbing or squatting movements.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'In managing OA, why is "low-impact" exercise preferred?',o:['It is less boring than high-impact exercise','It avoids further mechanical damage to the cartilage','It requires no equipment','It burns no calories'],a:1,e:`Low-impact exercise is preferred in OA because it strengthens supporting muscles and improves cardiovascular fitness while avoiding further mechanical damage to already compromised articular cartilage.<br><br>Activities such as swimming, cycling, and walking generate beneficial muscle work without high peak joint reaction forces. Aerobic exercise improves balance and reduces tendency to fall, gains valuable in older OA patients independently.<br><br>Boredom is irrelevant to clinical recommendation; equipment requirements are not the rationale for low-impact preference; calorie burning still occurs with low-impact exercise though weight loss benefits OA through load reduction.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Paget’s disease of bone is primarily characterized by:',o:['Defective mineralization of osteoid','Autoimmune synovial inflammation','Excessive bone resorption followed by disorganized bone formation','Decreased osteoclast activity'],a:2,e:`Paget disease of bone is characterised by excessive osteoclast-mediated bone resorption followed by disorganised, accelerated osteoblast bone formation, producing structurally weak bone with abnormal architecture.<br><br>The disease passes through lytic, mixed, and sclerotic phases. Affected bone is enlarged, vascular, and prone to deformity and pathological fracture. Heredity and possibly paramyxovirus infection are implicated in pathogenesis.<br><br>Defective mineralisation of osteoid is osteomalacia, not Paget's; autoimmune synovial inflammation describes rheumatoid arthritis; decreased osteoclast activity defines osteopetrosis (marble bone disease), the opposite of the increased osteoclast turnover in Paget's.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which biochemical marker is most elevated in Paget’s disease?',o:['Alkaline phosphatase','Serum calcium','Creatinine','Serum phosphate'],a:0,e:`Alkaline phosphatase is markedly elevated in Paget disease, reflecting intense osteoblast activity during the bone-formation phase that follows accelerated osteoclastic resorption in affected bone segments.<br><br>Serum ALP often rises to several times the upper normal limit and parallels disease activity. It is the most useful biochemical marker for diagnosis, monitoring response to bisphosphonate therapy, and detecting relapse in Paget's.<br><br>Serum calcium is typically normal in Paget's because resorption and formation are coupled; creatinine is unaffected unless renal disease coexists; serum phosphate is also normal in uncomplicated Paget disease without other co-morbidities.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A classic radiographic feature of Paget’s disease of skull is:',o:['Ground glass appearance','Cotton wool appearance','Salt and pepper skull','Sunburst pattern'],a:1,e:`Cotton wool appearance of the skull is a classic radiographic feature of Paget disease, produced by patchy areas of dense sclerotic bone interspersed with osteolytic regions in the calvarium.<br><br>Earlier in disease the skull shows osteoporosis circumscripta, a well-defined lytic area, which evolves into the mixed cotton wool pattern. The skull thickens, particularly the outer table, leaving the inner cortex spared.<br><br>Ground glass appearance suggests fibrous dysplasia of bone; salt and pepper skull is seen in hyperparathyroidism with subperiosteal resorption; sunburst pattern is characteristic of osteosarcoma with periosteal new bone.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common complication of Paget’s disease is:',o:['Septic arthritis','Osteomyelitis','Osteoporosis','Pathological fractures'],a:3,e:`Pathological fractures are the most common complication of Paget disease, occurring through structurally weak woven bone laid down disorganised during the formation phase of disease activity.<br><br>Fractures often involve the femur, tibia, and humerus, frequently as transverse banana-shaped fractures across bowed long bones. Bone pain and deformity (anterior tibial bowing, frontal skull bossing) precede fracture in many patients clinically.<br><br>Septic arthritis is unrelated to Paget's; osteomyelitis is uncommon; osteoporosis is a separate metabolic bone disease characterised by reduced bone mass rather than the disordered remodelling and increased mass of Paget's disease.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Paget’s disease affecting skull commonly leads to:',o:['Conductive hearing loss','Facial paralysis only','Sensorineural hearing loss','Vision loss only'],a:2,e:`Sensorineural hearing loss is the typical Paget complication of skull involvement, due to compression of the eighth cranial nerve and cochlear capsule by enlarged, thickened temporal bone.<br><br>The mechanism includes both direct nerve compression and otic capsule remodelling that disturbs cochlear function. Cranial nerve palsies, basilar invagination, and platybasia may also occur with extensive skull base involvement in Paget's.<br><br>Conductive hearing loss alone is uncommon; isolated facial paralysis without hearing loss is atypical for Paget's; vision loss alone is rare and would imply optic foramen narrowing, less common than auditory complications.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'First-line treatment of symptomatic Paget’s disease is:',o:['Steroids','Calcium supplements','Methotrexate','Bisphosphonates'],a:3,e:`Bisphosphonates are first-line treatment for symptomatic Paget disease; intravenous zoledronate is preferred, providing prolonged biochemical remission and symptomatic relief from a single annual dose typically.<br><br>Bisphosphonates inhibit osteoclast activity, normalising bone turnover and lowering alkaline phosphatase. Treatment indications include bone pain, neurological complications, planned orthopaedic surgery, and disease in weight-bearing bones at risk of deformity or fracture.<br><br>Steroids do not modify Paget bone turnover; calcium supplements do not address the underlying remodelling abnormality; methotrexate is a DMARD for inflammatory arthritis and has no role in metabolic bone diseases like Paget's.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'In Paget’s disease, serum calcium is usually:',o:['Undetectable','Normal','Markedly elevated','Low'],a:1,e:`Serum calcium is usually normal in Paget disease because bone resorption and formation remain tightly coupled, despite both processes being markedly accelerated above normal physiological turnover rates.<br><br>Hypercalcaemia may occur transiently with prolonged immobilisation, when resorption proceeds without compensatory formation. Otherwise calcium and phosphate remain within reference range, and ALP elevation alone reflects active disease in uncomplicated cases biochemically.<br><br>Markedly elevated calcium points to malignancy, hyperparathyroidism, or sarcoidosis rather than Paget's; low calcium suggests vitamin D deficiency or hypoparathyroidism; undetectable calcium is incompatible with life regardless of bone disease status.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The increased warmth over affected bone in Paget’s disease is due to:',o:['Increased vascularity','Infection','Bone infarction','Nerve compression'],a:0,e:`Increased warmth over bone affected by Paget disease results from markedly increased vascularity of pagetic bone, with arteriovenous shunting and high blood flow through the metabolically active tissue.<br><br>The hypervascularity is so pronounced that high-output cardiac failure may develop in widespread Paget disease. Local warmth is detectable by palpation alone and contrasts with cooler temperature of normal adjacent bone.<br><br>Infection is uncommon in Paget bone and would produce systemic features; bone infarction causes pain rather than warmth; nerve compression produces neurological symptoms but does not raise local skin temperature over the bone.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A feared malignant transformation of Paget’s disease is:',o:['Ewing sarcoma','Fibrosarcoma','Osteosarcoma','Chondrosarcoma'],a:2,e:`Osteosarcoma is the feared malignant transformation of Paget disease, occurring in less than one percent of patients but carrying a uniformly poor prognosis once it develops.<br><br>New severe bone pain or a soft tissue mass over a previously stable Paget site should raise suspicion. Radiographs show a destructive lesion with cortical breach and soft tissue extension, requiring urgent imaging and biopsy.<br><br>Ewing sarcoma is a primary malignancy of children and young adults unrelated to Paget's; chondrosarcoma rarely complicates Paget's; fibrosarcoma is far less common than osteosarcoma in Paget malignant transformation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Paget’s disease most commonly affects:',o:['Pelvis and femur','Ribs only','Hands','Clavicle only'],a:0,e:`Paget disease most commonly affects the pelvis and femur, followed by the lumbar spine, skull, and tibia, typically in patients over 55 with monostotic or polyostotic distribution.<br><br>The disease often remains asymptomatic and is discovered incidentally on radiographs or as raised alkaline phosphatase. When symptomatic, bone pain, deformity, or fracture brings the patient to medical attention requiring further investigation.<br><br>Ribs alone are uncommon as sole site; hand involvement is rare since Paget's prefers axial skeleton and proximal long bones; clavicle alone as sole site is highly unusual in clinical practice.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Osteopetrosis results from:',o:['Collagen defect','Defective osteoclast-mediated bone resorption','Vitamin D deficiency','Increased osteoblast activity'],a:1,e:`Osteopetrosis results from defective osteoclast-mediated bone resorption due to mutations affecting the carbonic anhydrase II enzyme or proton pumps required for the acidic resorption microenvironment.<br><br>Without adequate resorption, primary bone is not remodelled into mature lamellar bone, producing dense but structurally weak skeletons. Inheritance is autosomal recessive (severe infantile) or autosomal dominant (milder adult) form clinically.<br><br>Collagen defects cause osteogenesis imperfecta, not osteopetrosis; vitamin D deficiency causes osteomalacia and rickets; increased osteoblast activity does not occur in osteopetrosis where the primary lesion is in osteoclast function.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Bones in osteopetrosis appear on X-ray as:',o:['Osteopenic','Radiolucent','Lytic lesions','Marble-like dense bones'],a:3,e:`Bones in osteopetrosis appear marble-like and densely sclerotic on radiography, with loss of normal corticomedullary differentiation and obliteration of the medullary cavity by excessive primary spongiosa.<br><br>Erlenmeyer flask deformity of long bones, bone-in-bone appearance of vertebrae, and dense skull base are classic radiographic findings. Despite radiographic density, the disorganised bone is brittle and prone to pathological fracture.<br><br>Osteopenic appearance describes osteoporosis, the opposite finding; radiolucency suggests reduced bone density; lytic lesions characterise multiple myeloma or metastases, not the diffuse sclerosis of osteopetrosis seen on plain radiography typically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The anemia seen in osteopetrosis occurs due to:',o:['Marrow space obliteration','Iron deficiency','Blood loss','Hemolysis'],a:0,e:`Anaemia in osteopetrosis occurs due to marrow space obliteration by excessive bone, leaving insufficient room for erythropoiesis and other haematopoietic activity in the medullary cavity.<br><br>Pancytopenia develops as marrow failure progresses. Extramedullary haematopoiesis in liver and spleen produces hepatosplenomegaly, an attempted compensation that is inadequate. Severe infantile cases require haematopoietic stem cell transplantation for cure of marrow failure.<br><br>Iron deficiency is unrelated to the marrow-space obliteration mechanism; blood loss is not characteristic; haemolysis would cause indirect hyperbilirubinaemia and reticulocytosis, neither of which feature in the marrow-failure anaemia of osteopetrosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hepatosplenomegaly in osteopetrosis is due to:',o:['Infection','Extramedullary hematopoiesis','Portal hypertension','Fat deposition'],a:1,e:`Hepatosplenomegaly in osteopetrosis is due to extramedullary haematopoiesis, as the obliterated marrow cavity drives haematopoietic stem cells to colonise the liver, spleen, and lymph nodes.<br><br>These extramedullary sites attempt to compensate for failing marrow function. The compensation is incomplete, leaving patients with persistent cytopenias. Splenomegaly may also contribute to thrombocytopenia and anaemia through hypersplenism in advanced cases clinically.<br><br>Infection causes hepatomegaly through hepatitis but is not the primary mechanism in osteopetrosis; portal hypertension is unrelated; fat deposition produces steatosis, a process unrelated to the haematopoietic compensation seen in osteopetrosis here.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A common cranial nerve complication of osteopetrosis is:',o:['Facial nerve palsy only','Vagus nerve injury','Optic nerve compression','Hypoglossal palsy only'],a:2,e:`Optic nerve compression is a common cranial nerve complication of osteopetrosis as the dense, expanded skull narrows the optic foramina, leading to progressive visual loss.<br><br>Other cranial nerves including facial, auditory, and trigeminal may also be affected by skull base narrowing. Decompressive surgery is sometimes required, but bone marrow transplantation in infantile disease may halt progression.<br><br>Isolated facial nerve palsy is less typical than optic involvement; vagus injury is uncommon in this distribution; hypoglossal palsy alone is rare since multiple cranial nerves are usually affected in osteopetrotic skull base disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The definitive treatment for severe infantile osteopetrosis is:',o:['Radiation therapy','NSAIDs','Vitamin D therapy','Bone marrow transplantation'],a:3,e:`Bone marrow transplantation is the definitive treatment for severe infantile osteopetrosis, providing donor-derived osteoclasts that resorb bone normally and rescue marrow function before the disease becomes lethal.<br><br>Donor osteoclasts originate from haematopoietic stem cells, so HSCT replaces the defective osteoclast lineage entirely. Early transplantation before complications such as blindness and severe marrow failure improves outcomes substantially.<br><br>Radiation does not address osteoclast dysfunction; NSAIDs treat pain but not the underlying disease; vitamin D therapy worsens hypocalcaemia in some forms and does not correct the genetic osteoclast defect.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In osteopetrosis, fracture risk is:',o:['Increased despite dense bones','Normal','Only in elderly','Decreased'],a:0,e:`Fracture risk in osteopetrosis is paradoxically increased despite radiographically dense bones, because the disorganised primary bone is brittle and lacks the lamellar architecture providing mechanical resilience.<br><br>Without adequate osteoclastic remodelling, woven bone persists where mature lamellar bone should form. Repeated cycles of microdamage accumulate without repair, leaving bone strong in compression but weak in tension.<br><br>Normal fracture risk would not warrant the disease's name (marble bone disease); fractures occur in children, not just elderly; decreased fracture risk is the opposite of what occurs in this dense bone disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which lab finding is common in osteopetrosis?',o:['Leukocytosis','Pancytopenia','Polycythemia','Thrombocytosis'],a:1,e:`Pancytopenia is a common laboratory finding in osteopetrosis, reflecting marrow space obliteration with anaemia, neutropenia, and thrombocytopenia developing as bone progressively encroaches on the haematopoietic compartment.<br><br>Recurrent infections from neutropenia and bleeding from thrombocytopenia complicate severe disease alongside transfusion-dependent anaemia. The blood film may show teardrop poikilocytes and nucleated red cells reflecting extramedullary haematopoiesis in liver and spleen.<br><br>Leukocytosis is not characteristic; polycythaemia is the opposite of marrow failure; thrombocytosis is not seen since megakaryocytes share the same suppressed marrow environment as red and white cell precursors in the obliterated marrow.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Multiple myeloma is a malignancy of:',o:['Fibroblasts','Osteoclasts','T lymphocytes','Plasma cells'],a:3,e:`Multiple myeloma is a malignancy of plasma cells, the antibody-producing terminal differentiation stage of B lymphocytes; clonal expansion in marrow produces a single immunoglobulin or light chain.<br><br>Marrow plasma cells normally make up under 5 percent of cellularity; in myeloma they exceed 10 percent and dominate the marrow. CRAB features (hyperCalcaemia, Renal failure, Anaemia, Bone lesions) define symptomatic disease.<br><br>Fibroblasts populate connective tissue without immunoglobulin secretion; osteoclasts resorb bone and are activated indirectly in myeloma but are not the malignant cell; T lymphocytes do not produce immunoglobulin or rouleaux.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The classic CRAB feature includes all except:',o:['Anemia','Renal failure','Bradycardia','HyperCalcemia'],a:2,e:`The classic CRAB features of multiple myeloma are hyperCalcaemia, Renal failure, Anaemia, and Bone lesions; bradycardia is not part of the acronym or the typical disease pattern.<br><br>Each component reflects a distinct disease mechanism: cytokine-driven osteoclast activation causes lytic lesions and hypercalcaemia, light chain deposition damages the kidney, and marrow infiltration produces normocytic anaemia in symptomatic patients clinically requiring treatment.<br><br>Anaemia, renal failure, and hypercalcaemia are all CRAB components and so are not the exception; only bradycardia falls outside the CRAB framework, making it the correct exception in this question.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common immunoglobulin elevated in multiple myeloma is:',o:['IgA','IgE','IgM','IgG'],a:3,e:`IgG is the most common immunoglobulin elevated in multiple myeloma, accounting for about 55 percent of cases; IgA myeloma is next, with IgM, IgD, and IgE forms much rarer.<br><br>The malignant plasma cell clone secretes a monoclonal paraprotein detectable on serum protein electrophoresis as an M spike. Light chain only myeloma produces no intact immunoglobulin in serum but kappa or lambda light chains.<br><br>IgA myeloma is second in frequency, not first; IgM elevation typifies Waldenstrom macroglobulinaemia rather than classical myeloma; IgE myeloma is exceptionally rare and not the most common subtype encountered in practice.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Characteristic skull X-ray finding in multiple myeloma:',o:['Punched-out lytic lesions','Codfish vertebrae','Sunray appearance','Cotton wool appearance'],a:0,e:`Punched-out lytic lesions on skull radiography are characteristic of multiple myeloma; the lesions are well-circumscribed, sharply marginated, and lack the surrounding sclerotic rim of benign processes.<br><br>Cytokines including RANK ligand, IL-6, and DKK1 secreted by myeloma cells stimulate osteoclast activity and inhibit osteoblasts, producing pure lytic lesions without reactive new bone. Bone scintigraphy is therefore unreliable; whole-body MRI or PET preferred.<br><br>Codfish vertebrae appear in osteomalacia and osteoporosis with biconcave deformity; sunray appearance is osteosarcoma; cotton wool skull is Paget disease, not the punched-out pattern characteristic of myeloma bone destruction radiographically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Bence Jones proteins are detected in:',o:['CSF','Saliva','Urine','Blood'],a:2,e:`Bence Jones proteins are immunoglobulin light chains (kappa or lambda) detected in urine of multiple myeloma patients; serum protein electrophoresis often misses them because they are rapidly filtered.<br><br>Free light chains pass through the glomerulus and overwhelm proximal tubular reabsorption. Serum free light chain assay has largely replaced urine electrophoresis. Light chain deposition causes myeloma cast nephropathy.<br><br>CSF Bence Jones detection is not a standard test; saliva is not a sample medium for paraprotein analysis; serum lacks Bence Jones because rapid renal clearance moves them into urine before serum levels rise.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The renal damage in multiple myeloma is mainly due to:',o:['Glomerulonephritis','Light chain deposition','Calcium oxalate stones','Infection'],a:1,e:`Renal damage in multiple myeloma is mainly due to light chain deposition forming intratubular casts (myeloma cast nephropathy), which obstruct nephrons and trigger interstitial inflammation and tubular injury.<br><br>Hypercalcaemia, dehydration, hyperuricaemia, NSAID use, and amyloid deposition compound the renal injury. Up to half of patients have renal impairment at diagnosis. Aggressive hydration and disease-directed therapy are critical for renal recovery.<br><br>Glomerulonephritis is uncommon in classical myeloma; calcium oxalate stones are unrelated to paraprotein-driven injury; infection contributes to mortality but is not the primary mechanism of the renal damage seen in multiple myeloma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Rouleaux formation on blood smear suggests:',o:['Multiple myeloma','Leukemia','Hemophilia','Thalassemia'],a:0,e:`Rouleaux formation on blood smear suggests multiple myeloma; high circulating paraprotein neutralises red cell surface charge, allowing erythrocytes to stack like coins on the peripheral blood film.<br><br>Rouleaux is also seen in other paraproteinaemias and high acute-phase states with elevated fibrinogen. Combined with very high ESR, anaemia, hypercalcaemia, or renal impairment, it strongly raises suspicion for myeloma.<br><br>Leukaemia produces blasts and immature white cells rather than rouleaux; haemophilia is a coagulation disorder without rouleaux; thalassaemia shows microcytic hypochromic red cells with target forms, not rouleaux on the peripheral smear.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Bone pain in multiple myeloma is typically:',o:['Only after exercise','Only in morning','Worse at night and persistent','Migratory'],a:2,e:`Bone pain in multiple myeloma is typically worse at night, persistent, and progressive, often not relieved by rest, reflecting active osteolytic destruction in vertebrae, ribs, pelvis, and proximal long bones.<br><br>Sudden severe back pain may indicate vertebral compression fracture. Pain can also reflect spinal cord compression requiring emergency MRI and dexamethasone. The relentless quality helps distinguish it from mechanical osteoarthritic pain.<br><br>Pain only after exercise is mechanical and atypical for malignancy; morning-only pain suggests inflammatory arthritis; migratory pain is uncharacteristic of bone marrow malignancy where lesions are fixed and progressive.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hypercalcemia in multiple myeloma results from:',o:['Vitamin D toxicity','Increased PTH','Renal failure','Bone destruction'],a:3,e:`Hypercalcaemia in multiple myeloma results from bone destruction; myeloma cell-secreted cytokines including RANK ligand and IL-6 activate osteoclasts that release calcium from extensive lytic skeletal lesions.<br><br>Elevated calcium produces polyuria, dehydration, constipation, confusion, and worsening renal impairment, often requiring urgent rehydration and bisphosphonate or denosumab treatment. Severe symptomatic hypercalcaemia is a medical emergency in untreated myeloma at presentation often.<br><br>Vitamin D toxicity is a different cause of hypercalcaemia; PTH is suppressed in myeloma hypercalcaemia rather than elevated; renal failure usually causes hypocalcaemia from phosphate retention, not the hypercalcaemia of myeloma bone disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'ESR in multiple myeloma is:',o:['Variable only','Very high','Low','Normal'],a:1,e:`ESR is markedly elevated in multiple myeloma, often exceeding 100 mm per hour; high circulating paraprotein increases red cell aggregation and accelerates sedimentation in the Westergren tube.<br><br>ESR is a useful screening clue but lacks specificity since it rises in many inflammatory and malignant conditions. Serum and urine protein electrophoresis with immunofixation, free light chains, and bone marrow biopsy confirm diagnosis.<br><br>Variable ESR is non-specific and not a typical pattern; low ESR is the opposite of the rouleaux-driven elevation; normal ESR would be unusual in symptomatic myeloma and should prompt reconsideration of the diagnosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Most common site of involvement in multiple myeloma:',o:['Axial skeleton','Foot bones','Small bones of hand','Skull base only'],a:0,e:`The axial skeleton (vertebrae, ribs, skull, pelvis, proximal femur, and humerus) is the most commonly involved site in multiple myeloma, mirroring red marrow distribution in adults.<br><br>Vertebral compression fractures, rib lytic lesions, and proximal femur involvement contribute to morbidity and pathological fracture risk. Whole-body imaging with low-dose CT, MRI, or PET-CT identifies lesions missed on plain radiographs.<br><br>Foot bones contain little red marrow and are uncommon sites; small hand bones are similarly spared; skull base alone is too restricted as the disease distributes widely through axial red marrow areas in most patients.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A monoclonal spike on electrophoresis is called:',o:['S wave','Q complex','P spike','M spike'],a:3,e:`A monoclonal spike on serum protein electrophoresis is called an M spike; it represents a single immunoglobulin produced in excess by the malignant plasma cell clone, migrating as a narrow band.<br><br>Quantifying the M protein helps assess disease burden and monitor treatment response. Immunofixation identifies the heavy and light chain types, classifying myeloma as IgG kappa, IgA lambda, or other variants.<br><br>S wave is a cardiac ECG term unrelated to electrophoresis; Q complex does not exist in this context; P spike is not standard for the monoclonal band on serum protein electrophoresis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Vertebral collapse in multiple myeloma causes:',o:['Scoliosis only','Lordosis','Kyphosis','Flat back only'],a:2,e:`Vertebral collapse in multiple myeloma causes kyphosis; anterior wedging of weakened vertebral bodies tilts the spine forward, producing dorsal curvature and progressive height loss in elderly patients.<br><br>Lytic destruction of trabecular bone weakens vertebrae which collapse under axial load. Multiple thoracic compression fractures produce the typical dowager-type kyphotic deformity, sometimes accompanied by spinal cord compression in advanced disease.<br><br>Scoliosis (option A) is lateral spinal curvature, not the typical compression deformity; lordosis (option B) is exaggerated lumbar curvature, opposite to vertebral wedging; flat back alone (option D) misses the active progressive deformity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Most common cause of death in multiple myeloma:',o:['MI','Infection','Stroke','Hemorrhage'],a:1,e:`Infection is the most common cause of death in multiple myeloma; suppression of normal immunoglobulin production by the malignant clone leaves patients vulnerable to encapsulated bacterial pathogens.<br><br>Functional hypogammaglobulinaemia, neutropenia from disease and chemotherapy, and impaired vaccine response all contribute. Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus, and Gram-negative organisms account for many fatal infections.<br><br>Myocardial infarction (option A) is not the leading cause despite cardiovascular comorbidity; stroke (option C) is uncommon as primary cause; haemorrhage (option D) from thrombocytopenia contributes but ranks below infectious mortality.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Bone lesions in multiple myeloma are:',o:['Calcified','Sclerotic','Lytic','Mixed'],a:2,e:`Bone lesions in multiple myeloma are lytic; cytokine-driven osteoclast activation produces pure lytic destruction without compensatory osteoblastic new bone formation, hence absent uptake on isotope bone scans.<br><br>Myeloma cells secrete RANK ligand, IL-6, and DKK1 which inhibit osteoblasts and stimulate osteoclasts. Whole-body MRI, low-dose CT, or PET-CT detect lesions missed on plain X-ray and assess marrow infiltration burden directly.<br><br>Calcified lesions (option A) are not characteristic; sclerotic lesions (option B) appear in osteoblastic metastases or POEMS syndrome rather than classical myeloma; mixed lesions (option D) are uncommon in pure myeloma bone disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Amyloidosis associated with multiple myeloma is due to:',o:['Complement proteins','Light chains','Albumin','Heavy chains'],a:1,e:`Amyloidosis associated with multiple myeloma is due to light chains; excess monoclonal kappa or lambda light chains misfold and deposit as amyloid fibrils, called AL amyloidosis.<br><br>Lambda light chains predominate. Deposition involves heart (cardiomyopathy), kidney (nephrotic syndrome), tongue (macroglossia), and peripheral nerves. Congo red shows apple-green birefringence under polarised light, confirming the diagnosis.<br><br>Complement proteins (option A) are not the amyloid substrate; albumin (option C) does not form amyloid; intact heavy chains (option D) rarely deposit, so heavy chain disease is a distinct entity from AL.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which lab finding supports multiple myeloma?',o:['Low globulin','Low total protein','High platelets','High total protein'],a:3,e:`High total protein supports multiple myeloma; the monoclonal paraprotein elevates total serum protein with disproportionately high globulin fraction relative to albumin on biochemistry panels.<br><br>The albumin-to-globulin ratio is reversed. A serum protein gap above 4 g/dL warrants paraprotein workup. Confirmation requires serum protein electrophoresis with immunofixation and free light chain assay.<br><br>Globulin is high, not low (option A); total protein is elevated, not low (option B); platelets (option C) are typically normal or reduced from marrow infiltration, never elevated as a supporting finding.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Plasmacytoma refers to:',o:['Solitary plasma cell tumor','Metastasis','Benign fibroma','Bone cyst'],a:0,e:`Plasmacytoma is a solitary plasma cell tumour, occurring as a single mass in bone or soft tissue, without the diffuse marrow infiltration seen in multiple myeloma.<br><br>Solitary plasmacytoma is potentially curable with local radiotherapy. Bone marrow must show no clonal plasma cells elsewhere. Many patients eventually progress to multiple myeloma over years requiring long-term surveillance.<br><br>Metastasis (option B) describes spread of any malignancy and is not specific; benign fibroma (option C) is a fibrous tumour without plasma cells; bone cyst (option D) is non-neoplastic fluid-filled cavity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hyperviscosity syndrome in myeloma causes:',o:['Polyuria only','Hypoglycemia','Hypertension','Blurred vision'],a:3,e:`Hyperviscosity syndrome in myeloma causes blurred vision; high circulating paraprotein increases serum viscosity, slowing retinal microcirculation and producing visual blurring with sausage-string retinal veins on fundoscopy.<br><br>Other features include headache, mucosal bleeding, confusion, vertigo, and high-output cardiac failure. Plasmapheresis provides rapid relief. Hyperviscosity is more common in IgM Waldenstrom macroglobulinaemia than classical myeloma.<br><br>Polyuria alone (option A) is non-specific and may reflect hypercalcaemia; hypoglycaemia (option B) is unrelated to paraprotein viscosity; hypertension (option C) is not a typical hyperviscosity feature, which causes flow stasis instead.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which investigation confirms multiple myeloma?',o:['ECG','Bone marrow biopsy','CT brain','ABG'],a:1,e:`Bone marrow biopsy confirms multiple myeloma; diagnosis requires demonstration of clonal plasma cells exceeding 10 percent of marrow cellularity together with end-organ damage or biomarkers.<br><br>Aspirate and trephine biopsy reveal sheets of atypical plasma cells with eccentric nuclei and perinuclear hof. Cytogenetics, flow cytometry, and FISH stratify risk. Imaging detects bone lesions.<br><br>ECG (option A) assesses cardiac rhythm and is irrelevant to myeloma diagnosis; CT brain (option C) has no role in marrow malignancy workup; arterial blood gas (option D) evaluates respiratory and acid-base status.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Osteolytic lesions in myeloma occur due to:',o:['Increased osteoclast activation','Increased osteoblast activity','Collagen mutation','Infection'],a:0,e:`Osteolytic lesions in myeloma occur due to increased osteoclast activation; RANK ligand and IL-6 secretion by myeloma cells drives osteoclast differentiation and resorptive activity in marrow.<br><br>Concurrent osteoblast inhibition by DKK1 (a Wnt pathway antagonist) prevents compensatory bone formation. Bisphosphonates and denosumab reduce skeletal events by inhibiting osteoclast function, forming key supportive therapy.<br><br>Increased osteoblast activity (option B) would produce sclerotic, not lytic, lesions; collagen mutations (option C) cause osteogenesis imperfecta rather than plasma cell malignancy; infection (option D) is not the mechanism of myeloma bone disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Anemia in multiple myeloma is mainly due to:',o:['Blood loss','Iron deficiency','Marrow infiltration','Hemolysis'],a:2,e:`Anaemia in multiple myeloma is mainly due to marrow infiltration; malignant plasma cells crowd out erythroid precursors while disease cytokines suppress effective erythropoiesis in residual marrow.<br><br>Erythropoietin response is also blunted by renal impairment from light chain damage and inflammatory cytokine release. Anaemia is normocytic and normochromic; transfusion or erythropoiesis-stimulating agents may be required.<br><br>Blood loss (option A) is not the primary mechanism; iron deficiency (option B) is uncommon as cause; haemolysis (option D) is rare in myeloma except with autoimmune phenomena, none of which dominate marrow infiltration.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with bone pain, anemia, and renal failure should be suspected of:',o:['Multiple myeloma','Rickets','Leukemia','Osteoporosis'],a:0,e:`Bone pain, anaemia, and renal failure should raise suspicion of multiple myeloma; this triad reflects three of the four CRAB criteria defining symptomatic plasma cell malignancy in older patients.<br><br>Hypercalcaemia frequently coexists, completing the CRAB tetrad. Initial workup includes serum protein electrophoresis, immunofixation, free light chains, marrow biopsy, and skeletal survey for diagnosis confirmation and staging.<br><br>Rickets (option B) affects children with vitamin D deficiency; leukaemia (option C) presents with cytopenias and circulating blasts but lacks lytic bone lesions; osteoporosis (option D) causes fragility fractures without renal failure.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The most sensitive test for detecting monoclonal proteins:',o:['Urinalysis','Serum protein electrophoresis','CBC','X-ray'],a:1,e:`Serum protein electrophoresis is the most sensitive routine test for detecting monoclonal proteins; the M spike appears as a tall narrow band in the gamma globulin region on the densitometric trace.<br><br>Immunofixation electrophoresis identifies the heavy and light chain class. Serum free light chain assay detects light chain only myeloma. Together these provide highest sensitivity for paraprotein detection.<br><br>Urinalysis (option A) detects Bence Jones proteins but is less sensitive than serum testing; CBC (option C) shows anaemia but no paraprotein; X-ray (option D) detects bone lesions but cannot identify monoclonal proteins.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Beta-2 microglobulin level in myeloma indicates:',o:['Calcium level','Liver function','Infection','Tumor burden/prognosis'],a:3,e:`Beta-2 microglobulin level in myeloma indicates tumour burden and prognosis; it is a component of the International Staging System (ISS), with higher levels predicting shorter survival and worse outcomes.<br><br>ISS combines beta-2 microglobulin and albumin to define stages I-III. Revised ISS adds cytogenetics and LDH. Higher beta-2 microglobulin reflects greater tumour mass and impaired renal clearance, predicting more aggressive disease.<br><br>Calcium level (option A) is measured separately and reflects bone resorption; liver function (option B) is unrelated; infection (option C) is suggested by inflammatory markers and cultures, not by beta-2 microglobulin levels.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Recurrent infections in myeloma occur due to:',o:['Neutropenia only','High platelets','Suppressed normal immunoglobulins','Low calcium'],a:2,e:`Recurrent infections in myeloma occur due to suppressed normal immunoglobulins; the malignant clone produces a single ineffective paraprotein while suppressing other immunoglobulin classes through marrow microenvironment effects.<br><br>Functional hypogammaglobulinaemia leaves patients vulnerable to encapsulated bacteria. Pneumococcal, Haemophilus, and meningococcal vaccinations are recommended though response is suboptimal. Prophylactic intravenous immunoglobulin may be considered in selected patients.<br><br>Neutropenia alone (option A) contributes but is not the dominant mechanism; high platelets (option B) are not a feature; low calcium (option D) does not predispose to infection and is uncommon in myeloma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Bone marrow plasma cells >10% suggests:',o:['Osteoporosis','Multiple myeloma','Leukemoid reaction','Polycythemia'],a:1,e:`Bone marrow plasma cells exceeding 10 percent strongly suggests multiple myeloma; together with end-organ damage or myeloma-defining biomarkers, this threshold establishes the diagnosis of symptomatic disease.<br><br>Smouldering myeloma has more than 10 percent plasma cells without end-organ damage. MGUS has under 10 percent. Threshold quantitation by trephine biopsy, flow cytometry, and immunohistochemistry distinguishes these entities.<br><br>Osteoporosis (option A) shows reduced bone mass without plasma cell increase; leukemoid reaction (option C) shows mature granulocytic hyperplasia, not plasma cells; polycythaemia (option D) features erythroid expansion, distinct from plasma cell proliferation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A compression fracture in elderly with lytic lesions suggests:',o:['Trauma only','Osteoarthritis','Metastasis','Multiple myeloma'],a:3,e:`Compression fracture in an elderly patient with lytic lesions strongly suggests multiple myeloma; lytic destruction of vertebral trabeculae weakens the body and predisposes to wedge collapse under axial load.<br><br>MRI distinguishes benign osteoporotic from malignant compression fractures by marrow signal pattern. Pathological fractures may be the presenting feature. Investigation includes paraprotein testing, free light chains, and marrow biopsy.<br><br>Trauma alone (option A) does not produce lytic lesions; osteoarthritis (option B) does not cause vertebral lytic lesions; metastasis (option C) is plausible but myeloma is more typical with multiple punched-out lytic lesions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Treatment regimen commonly includes:',o:['Chemotherapy + steroids','NSAIDs only','Antibiotics only','Insulin'],a:0,e:`Treatment regimens for multiple myeloma commonly include chemotherapy combined with steroids; modern triplets add proteasome inhibitors (bortezomib) or immunomodulatory drugs (lenalidomide) to dexamethasone backbones.<br><br>Autologous stem cell transplantation follows induction in fit patients. Maintenance lenalidomide prolongs remission. Daratumumab (anti-CD38 monoclonal antibody) and other novel agents have transformed outcomes, with median survival now exceeding seven years in many treated patients.<br><br>NSAIDs alone (option B) treat bone pain but not the malignancy; antibiotics alone (option C) address infections, not myeloma; insulin (option D) is endocrine therapy unrelated to plasma cell malignancy treatment principles entirely.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Light chain deposition disease affects mainly:',o:['Brain','Lung','Kidney','Liver'],a:2,e:`Light chain deposition disease affects mainly the kidney; non-fibrillar deposition of monoclonal kappa (most often) light chains in glomerular and tubular basement membranes produces progressive renal failure.<br><br>Unlike AL amyloidosis, deposits do not stain with Congo red. Electron microscopy shows granular electron-dense deposits along basement membranes. Treatment targets the underlying clone with chemotherapy similar to myeloma.<br><br>Brain (option A) is rarely involved; lung (option B) is not a primary target; liver (option D) involvement is uncommon and usually subclinical, contrasting the predominant and clinically significant kidney involvement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Increased alkaline phosphatase in Paget’s disease reflects:',o:['Renal disease','Increased bone turnover','Anemia','Liver failure'],a:1,e:`Increased alkaline phosphatase in Paget disease reflects increased bone turnover; intense osteoblast activity during the formation phase elevates ALP markedly, often several times the upper normal limit.<br><br>Serum ALP parallels disease activity and falls with effective bisphosphonate treatment. It is the most useful biochemical marker for diagnosis, monitoring response, and detecting relapse. Calcium and phosphate remain normal.<br><br>Renal disease (option A) raises creatinine and phosphate, not ALP; anaemia (option C) is unrelated to ALP elevation; liver failure (option D) raises ALP through cholestasis but Paget's elevation is bone-specific.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The bone pain in Paget’s disease is due to:',o:['Muscle spasm only','Infection','Microfractures and expansion of bone','Vitamin deficiency'],a:2,e:`Bone pain in Paget disease arises from microfractures and bone expansion; structurally weak woven bone develops cortical microfissures, and enlargement of bone stretches periosteum and adjacent joint capsules.<br><br>Pain may also reflect secondary osteoarthritis in joints adjacent to deformed bone, nerve compression syndromes, or rarely sarcomatous transformation. Bisphosphonate therapy reduces bone turnover and typically improves pain.<br><br>Muscle spasm alone (option A) does not explain the persistent bone pain; infection (option B) is uncommon in Paget bone; vitamin deficiency (option D) causes osteomalacia rather than Paget's microfracture pain.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A 24-year-old female presents with a 2-month history of joint pain, a rash across her cheeks that spares the nasolabial folds, and pleuritic chest pain. Laboratory testing shows a positive ANA with a titer of 1:640. Which of the following is the most specific next test to confirm the diagnosis of Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)?',o:['Anti-histone antibodies','Rheumatoid factor','Anti-centromere antibodies','Anti-dsDNA antibodies'],a:3,e:`Anti-dsDNA antibodies are highly specific for SLE and indicate active disease, particularly lupus nephritis; titres often correlate with disease activity and renal involvement on serial monitoring.<br><br>ANA is sensitive but not specific. The classic SLE laboratory triad is positive ANA, anti-dsDNA, and anti-Smith. Low complement (C3, C4, CH50) accompanies active disease as immune complex consumption proceeds.<br><br>Anti-histone (option A) is sensitive for drug-induced lupus rather than idiopathic SLE; rheumatoid factor (option B) is non-specific and characterises rheumatoid arthritis; anti-centromere (option C) is associated with limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 30-year-old woman with a history of SLE presents with new-onset swelling of her legs and frothy urine. Urinalysis reveals 4+ protein and red blood cell casts. What is the most appropriate next step to guide management?',o:['Perform a renal biopsy','Check serum uric acid levels','Order a 24-hour urine collection for cortisol','Start high-dose oral Ibuprofen'],a:0,e:`Renal biopsy is the most appropriate next step when SLE patients develop nephritic features; histological class guides immunosuppressive intensity, with diffuse proliferative (Class IV) requiring aggressive therapy.<br><br>Lupus nephritis is glomerular deposition of anti-DNA immune complexes. Most common and severe type is diffuse proliferative. Biopsy informs treatment with mycophenolate or cyclophosphamide induction followed by maintenance.<br><br>Serum uric acid (option B) is irrelevant to lupus nephritis; 24-hour urinary cortisol (option C) tests for Cushing syndrome; high-dose oral ibuprofen (option D) worsens renal function in active glomerulonephritis and is contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Ten days after receiving a dose of intravenous penicillin for an infection, a patient develops fever, a generalized urticarial rash, and painful, swollen joints. Lab results show low complement levels (C3 and C4). What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Henoch-Schönlein purpura','Acute Rheumatic Fever','Serum Sickness','Anaphylaxis'],a:2,e:`Serum sickness presents 7-14 days after antigen exposure with fever, urticarial rash, polyarthralgia, and lymphadenopathy; complement consumption produces low C3 and C4 levels during the active phase.<br><br>Mechanism is type III hypersensitivity with circulating immune complexes depositing in skin, joints, and kidneys. Penicillin, cefaclor, and heterologous antisera are classical triggers. Symptoms resolve spontaneously in 1-2 weeks.<br><br>Henoch-Schonlein purpura (option A) is IgA vasculitis with palpable purpura following respiratory infection; acute rheumatic fever (option B) follows streptococcal pharyngitis; anaphylaxis (option D) is immediate IgE-mediated, not delayed.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following mechanisms is responsible for the clinical manifestations of Serum Sickness?',o:['Type III hypersensitivity (Immune complex deposition)','Type IV hypersensitivity (Delayed T-cell mediated)','Type I hypersensitivity (IgE mediated)','Type II hypersensitivity (Cytotoxic)'],a:0,e:`Serum sickness is a type III hypersensitivity reaction; circulating immune complexes formed between exogenous antigen and host antibody deposit in vessel walls, fixing complement and recruiting neutrophils.<br><br>Vessel wall damage produces vasculitis, glomerulonephritis, arthritis, and rash. Low complement levels reflect consumption. Resolution occurs as antigen is cleared. Drugs (especially penicillins, cefaclor) are common modern triggers.<br><br>Type IV (option B) is delayed cell-mediated as in contact dermatitis; type I (option C) is IgE-mediated immediate hypersensitivity (anaphylaxis); type II (option D) is cytotoxic antibody-mediated as in haemolytic transfusion reactions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 45-year-old woman complains of skin thickening on her fingers extending to her wrists, difficulty swallowing, and fingers that turn blue then white in the cold. She has multiple "spider veins" on her face. Which antibody is most likely to be positive?',o:['Anti-Jo-1','Anti-Smith','Anti-Scl-70 (topoisomerase I)','Anti-centromere'],a:3,e:`Anti-centromere antibody is most likely positive in this CREST-pattern presentation; limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis with calcinosis, Raynaud, esophageal dysmotility, sclerodactyly, and telangiectasia carries this antibody association.<br><br>Limited scleroderma involves skin distal to elbows and knees plus face. Disease course is more benign than diffuse systemic sclerosis. Pulmonary arterial hypertension is the major late complication and leading cause of mortality.<br><br>Anti-Jo-1 (option A) marks polymyositis with antisynthetase syndrome; anti-Smith (option B) is specific for SLE; anti-Scl-70 (option C) is associated with diffuse systemic sclerosis with widespread skin involvement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with systemic sclerosis presents with severe hypertension (190/110 mmHg) and rapidly rising creatinine. Which medication is the treatment of choice for this "Scleroderma Renal Crisis"?',o:['Furosemide','Lisinopril (ACE inhibitor)','Propranolol','Prednisone'],a:1,e:`Lisinopril (ACE inhibitor) is the treatment of choice for scleroderma renal crisis; ACE inhibition reverses the renin-angiotensin overactivation driving the malignant hypertension and microangiopathic injury.<br><br>Scleroderma renal crisis presents with severe hypertension, rapidly rising creatinine, microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, and thrombocytopenia. Prompt ACE inhibitor therapy has transformed prognosis from uniformly fatal to recoverable.<br><br>Furosemide (option A) does not address renin-angiotensin pathology; propranolol (option C) reduces blood pressure but does not target the underlying mechanism; prednisone (option D) actually precipitates renal crisis at high doses.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A 38-year-old female presents with dry eyes and a dry mouth, describing a "gritty" sensation in her eyes. Physical exam shows enlarged parotid glands. Which test would provide a definitive diagnosis for Sjogren\'s Syndrome?',o:['Anti-CCP antibody','Schirmer’s test','Sialography','Minor salivary gland biopsy'],a:3,e:`Minor salivary gland biopsy provides definitive diagnosis of Sjogren syndrome; lymphocytic foci (focus score over 1) in labial gland tissue confirm the autoimmune exocrinopathy histologically.<br><br>Sjogren is characterised by destruction of exocrine glands by lymphocytic infiltrates, predominantly affecting females 40-60. Findings include keratoconjunctivitis sicca, xerostomia, antibodies SS-A (anti-Ro) and SS-B (anti-La).<br><br>Anti-CCP (option A) is rheumatoid arthritis-specific; Schirmer test (option B) measures tear production but is supportive rather than definitive; sialography (option C) shows ductal abnormalities supportively but does not confirm at tissue level.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD) is characterized by clinical features of SLE, systemic sclerosis, and polymyositis. Which autoantibody is the defining laboratory marker for MCTD?',o:['Anti-La/SSB','Anti-double stranded DNA','Anti-U1 RNP','Anti-Ro/SSA'],a:2,e:`Anti-U1 RNP is the defining laboratory marker for mixed connective tissue disease; high titres of this antibody alongside overlap clinical features distinguish MCTD from undifferentiated connective tissue disease.<br><br>MCTD shows features of SLE, systemic sclerosis, and polymyositis. Anti-U1 RNP produces a speckled ANA pattern. Pulmonary arterial hypertension is the leading cause of mortality in established disease.<br><br>Anti-La/SSB (option A) is associated with Sjogren syndrome; anti-dsDNA (option B) is specific for SLE rather than overlap syndrome; anti-Ro/SSA (option D) is associated with Sjogren and neonatal lupus, not MCTD.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 28-year-old woman with SLE is planning a pregnancy. She has a history of two mid-term miscarriages. Which laboratory finding would increase her risk of venous thromboembolism and pregnancy loss?',o:['Anti-Smith antibody','Lupus anticoagulant','Elevated ESR','Low C3/C4 levels'],a:1,e:`Lupus anticoagulant indicates antiphospholipid syndrome and increases risk of venous thromboembolism, arterial thrombosis, and recurrent pregnancy loss in this SLE patient planning conception.<br><br>Diagnosis based on history of thrombosis or spontaneous abortion plus laboratory findings of lupus anticoagulant, anticardiolipin, anti-beta2 glycoprotein antibodies. Treat with anticoagulation; pregnancy requires aspirin and heparin together.<br><br>Anti-Smith (option A) is highly specific for SLE but does not predict thrombosis; elevated ESR (option C) is non-specific inflammation; low C3/C4 (option D) reflects active SLE flare but not procoagulant tendency.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 50-year-old female with Systemic Sclerosis (diffuse type) develops progressive shortness of breath. Pulmonary function tests show a restrictive pattern and a decreased DLCO. What is the most likely underlying cause?',o:['Interstitial Lung Disease','Pulmonary Embolism','Bronchial Asthma','Alveolar Hemorrhage'],a:0,e:`Interstitial lung disease is the most likely cause; diffuse systemic sclerosis is associated with restrictive lung disease (interstitial fibrosis), now the most common cause of death in this disease.<br><br>Pulmonary function tests show restrictive pattern with reduced DLCO. HRCT reveals nonspecific or usual interstitial pneumonia patterns. Mycophenolate or cyclophosphamide may slow progression. Anti-Scl-70 predicts higher risk.<br><br>Pulmonary embolism (option B) is acute rather than progressive; bronchial asthma (option C) shows obstructive pattern with bronchodilator response; alveolar haemorrhage (option D) presents with haemoptysis and acute infiltrates.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a classic component of the CREST syndrome in limited scleroderma?',o:['Photosensitivity','Esophageal dysmotility','Renal failure','Malar rash'],a:1,e:`Esophageal dysmotility is a classic component of CREST syndrome; smooth muscle fibrosis and atrophy of the lower oesophageal sphincter and distal oesophagus produce reflux, dysphagia, and motility disorders.<br><br>CREST stands for Calcinosis, Raynaud phenomenon, Esophageal dysmotility, Sclerodactyly, and Telangiectasia. The limited form follows a more benign course than diffuse disease and is associated with anti-centromere antibody.<br><br>Photosensitivity (option A) is a feature of SLE rather than scleroderma; renal failure (option C) is renal crisis of diffuse systemic sclerosis, not CREST; malar rash (option D) is the butterfly rash of SLE.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with SLE presents with fever and weight loss. Lab work shows leukopenia, thrombocytopenia, and positive anti-Smith antibodies. Which of the following is considered the most specific (though not the most sensitive) marker for SLE?',o:['Anti-Smith antibody','C-reactive protein (CRP)','Anti-nuclear antibody (ANA)','Anti-histone antibody'],a:0,e:`Anti-Smith antibody is specific (though not sensitive) for SLE; despite presence in only 30 percent of patients, its high specificity makes it a confirmatory marker.<br><br>ANA is sensitive but not specific. Anti-dsDNA is specific with poor prognosis (renal disease). Anti-Smith is specific without prognostic implication, directed against snRNPs. Together they satisfy the immunologic criterion.<br><br>CRP (option B) is a non-specific acute phase reactant; ANA (option C) is sensitive but not specific (false positives in healthy people); anti-histone (option D) is sensitive for drug-induced lupus rather than idiopathic SLE.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Patients with Sjogren’s syndrome have a significantly increased risk (approx. 40-fold) of developing which malignancy?',o:['Renal cell carcinoma','Squamous cell carcinoma of the tongue','B-cell Non-Hodgkin Lymphoma','Osteosarcoma'],a:2,e:`Sjogren syndrome carries approximately 40-fold increased risk of B-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma; chronic lymphocytic stimulation in salivary tissue can transform into mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) lymphoma.<br><br>MALT lymphoma may present as persistent or progressive parotid enlargement. Other risk markers include cryoglobulinaemia, low C4, and palpable purpura. Vigilance for new lymphadenopathy or salivary gland masses is essential.<br><br>Renal cell carcinoma (option A) is not associated with Sjogren syndrome; squamous cell carcinoma of tongue (option B) relates to smoking and HPV; osteosarcoma (option D) is a primary bone malignancy unrelated to autoimmune exocrinopathy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In a patient with drug-induced lupus caused by Hydralazine, which antibody is characteristically present?',o:['Anti-dsDNA','Anti-Jo-1','Anti-Scl-70','Anti-histone'],a:3,e:`Anti-histone antibody is characteristically present in drug-induced lupus, particularly with hydralazine or procainamide as the offending agent; the antibody is sensitive for this drug-related entity.<br><br>Drug-induced lupus typically lacks renal and central nervous system involvement seen in idiopathic SLE. Symptoms resolve after stopping the drug. Anti-dsDNA is usually absent. Antinuclear antibody is positive.<br><br>Anti-dsDNA (option A) characterises idiopathic SLE with renal disease; anti-Jo-1 (option B) is associated with polymyositis and antisynthetase syndrome; anti-Scl-70 (option C) is associated with diffuse systemic sclerosis with lung disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 32-year-old woman with a history of Raynaud’s phenomenon and sclerodactyly presents with acute onset "watermelon stomach" (GAVE) on endoscopy and severe anemia. This is a complication of:',o:['SLE','Serum Sickness','Systemic Sclerosis','Sjogren’s syndrome'],a:2,e:`Watermelon stomach (gastric antral vascular ectasia) with severe anaemia in this Raynaud-sclerodactyly patient is a complication of systemic sclerosis; vascular dysplasia of the gastric antrum produces chronic blood loss.<br><br>Endoscopy shows characteristic linear red stripes radiating from the pylorus, resembling watermelon striations. Argon plasma coagulation is effective. GAVE is one of several gastrointestinal manifestations of systemic sclerosis.<br><br>SLE (option A) does not cause watermelon stomach; serum sickness (option B) is a transient immune complex reaction without GI vascular ectasia; Sjogren syndrome (option D) affects exocrine glands rather than gastric vasculature.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is the standard initial treatment for mild SLE (skin and joint symptoms)?',o:['Hydroxychloroquine','Cyclophosphamide','Rituximab','High-dose intravenous Methylprednisolone'],a:0,e:`Hydroxychloroquine is the standard initial treatment for mild SLE; it controls skin and joint symptoms, prevents disease flares, reduces thrombosis risk, and is recommended for all SLE patients.<br><br>Mechanism includes interference with toll-like receptor signalling and lysosomal function. Retinal toxicity necessitates annual ophthalmologic screening. NSAIDs and low-dose corticosteroids are added for symptom control.<br><br>Cyclophosphamide (option B) is reserved for severe organ-threatening disease such as proliferative lupus nephritis; rituximab (option C) is used for refractory disease; high-dose intravenous methylprednisolone (option D) is reserved for severe flares.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with known Sjogren’s syndrome presents with purpura on the lower legs and arthralgia. Labs show a positive Rheumatoid Factor and low C4. What should be suspected?',o:['Secondary Osteoarthritis','Viral hepatitis only','Iron deficiency','Cryoglobulinemia'],a:3,e:`Cryoglobulinaemia should be suspected; type II mixed cryoglobulinaemia presenting with palpable purpura, arthralgia, and low C4 commonly complicates Sjogren syndrome and signals increased lymphoma risk.<br><br>Cryoglobulins precipitate at low temperatures and deposit in small vessels causing leukocytoclastic vasculitis. Hepatitis C is another common association. Skin biopsy confirms vasculitis. Treatment addresses the underlying cause and may include rituximab in Sjogren-related cases.<br><br>Secondary osteoarthritis (option A) does not produce purpura or low complement; viral hepatitis alone (option B) is incomplete without addressing cryoglobulin deposition; iron deficiency (option C) does not cause purpura or hypocomplementaemia.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which clinical feature helps distinguish Diffuse Cutaneous Systemic Sclerosis from Limited Cutaneous Systemic Sclerosis?',o:['Esophageal reflux','Skin thickening proximal to the elbows and knees','Raynaud’s phenomenon','Presence of ANA'],a:1,e:`Skin thickening proximal to the elbows and knees defines diffuse cutaneous systemic sclerosis; limited cutaneous disease confines skin involvement to the fingers and face distal to elbows and knees.<br><br>Diffuse scleroderma shows widespread skin involvement, rapid progression, and early visceral involvement. It is associated with anti-Scl-70 antibody and higher risk of interstitial lung disease and renal crisis.<br><br>Esophageal reflux (option A) occurs in both forms; Raynaud phenomenon (option C) is universal in scleroderma regardless of subtype; presence of ANA (option D) characterises both forms and is non-discriminating between diffuse and limited disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 22-year-old male develops a rash and joint pain after receiving horse-derived anti-thymocyte globulin. This is an example of:',o:['Serum Sickness','Contact dermatitis','Acute Graft-versus-host disease','Primary biliary cholangitis'],a:0,e:`Serum sickness is the diagnosis; horse-derived anti-thymocyte globulin is heterologous animal-derived antiserum, a classical trigger for type III hypersensitivity-mediated immune complex disease 7-14 days after exposure.<br><br>Symptoms include fever, urticarial or maculopapular rash, polyarthralgia, and lymphadenopathy. Low C3 and C4 reflect complement consumption. Treatment is supportive with antihistamines and corticosteroids; symptoms resolve as antigen clears.<br><br>Contact dermatitis (option B) is type IV hypersensitivity producing localised eczematous reaction; acute graft-versus-host disease (option C) follows allogeneic transplantation, not antiserum; primary biliary cholangitis (option D) is a chronic autoimmune liver disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Libman-Sacks endocarditis is a non-infectious vegetative endocarditis associated with:',o:['Sjogren’s Syndrome','Systemic Sclerosis','Mixed Connective Tissue Disease','Systemic Lupus Erythematosus'],a:3,e:`Libman-Sacks endocarditis is associated with systemic lupus erythematosus; non-bacterial verrucous thrombi form on mitral or aortic valves, classically positioned on either valve surface in active SLE.<br><br>Vegetations consist of fibrin and platelet thrombi without microorganisms. They may embolise, producing stroke or peripheral ischaemia, or distort valve function causing regurgitation. Antiphospholipid antibodies in SLE increase risk.<br><br>Sjogren syndrome (option A) does not cause valvular vegetations; systemic sclerosis (option B) affects pericardium and myocardium without Libman-Sacks lesions; mixed connective tissue disease (option C) shares features but eponymous endocarditis is SLE-specific.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 35-year-old female with Sjogren syndrome presents with dry mouth, tooth decay, and oral thrush. She has positive Anti-Ro (SSA) and Anti-La (SSB) antibodies. What is the most appropriate symptomatic management for her dry mouth?',o:['Oral corticosteroids','Antihistamines','Pilocarpine or Cevimeline','Broad-spectrum antibiotics'],a:2,e:`Pilocarpine or cevimeline are appropriate symptomatic management for dry mouth in Sjogren syndrome; these muscarinic agonists stimulate residual salivary gland tissue to increase saliva production.<br><br>Sjogren xerostomia from lymphocytic glandular destruction predisposes to dental caries, oral candidiasis, and gum disease. Hydration, sugar-free lozenges, fluoride toothpaste, and regular dental review complement pharmacological sialogogues. Severe cases may require salivary substitutes.<br><br>Oral corticosteroids (option A) do not address xerostomia symptomatically; antihistamines (option B) worsen dry mouth through anticholinergic effects; broad-spectrum antibiotics (option D) are reserved for established bacterial infection rather than routine xerostomia management.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following represents the "T" in the CREST syndrome acronym?',o:['Thrombocytopenia','Telangiectasia','Tendonitis','Thyroiditis'],a:1,e:`Telangiectasia represents the T in CREST; small dilated cutaneous vessels appear on face, lips, hands, and oral mucosa, particularly prominent in limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis.<br><br>CREST stands for Calcinosis, Raynaud phenomenon, Esophageal dysmotility, Sclerodactyly, and Telangiectasia. The limited cutaneous form follows a more benign course than diffuse systemic sclerosis. Pulmonary hypertension is the main late complication.<br><br>Thrombocytopenia (option A) is not in the acronym; tendonitis (option C) does not feature; thyroiditis (option D) may coexist but is not represented by the T in CREST, which denotes telangiectasia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with SLE has low C3 and C4 levels. This lab finding usually correlates with:',o:['Drug-induced lupus','Infection with Staphylococcus','Disease remission','Active disease flare, particularly lupus nephritis'],a:3,e:`Low C3 and C4 in SLE usually correlate with active disease flare, particularly lupus nephritis; immune complex formation consumes complement during active disease, reducing circulating levels measurably.<br><br>Falling complement and rising anti-dsDNA titres precede or accompany disease flares. Serial monitoring guides treatment intensity. Persistent hypocomplementaemia despite clinical quiescence may reflect ongoing subclinical inflammation requiring vigilance.<br><br>Drug-induced lupus (option A) typically has normal complement levels; staphylococcal infection (option B) does not produce hypocomplementaemia; disease remission (option C) is associated with normal or rising complement, opposite of low complement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The differential diagnosis for a Malar rash includes all of the following EXCEPT:',o:['Dermatomyositis','Discoid Lupus','Seborrheic dermatitis','Rosacea'],a:1,e:`Discoid lupus is the exception; discoid lupus erythematosus produces well-demarcated, scaly, scarring plaques rather than the smooth erythematous malar (butterfly) rash, distinguishing it morphologically from true malar rash.<br><br>Malar rash differential includes systemic lupus, dermatomyositis (with heliotrope rash sparing nasolabial folds), seborrheic dermatitis (greasy scaling), and rosacea (telangiectasias and pustules). Each differs in distribution, surface character, and accompanying features.<br><br>Dermatomyositis (option A) shares photosensitive malar distribution with shawl sign; seborrheic dermatitis (option C) involves nasolabial folds with greasy scale; rosacea (option D) features papules, pustules, and telangiectasias.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In systemic sclerosis, what is the primary cause of esophageal dysmotility?',o:['Nerve compression at the C-spine','Candida infection','Fibrosis of the smooth muscle and atrophy','Excessive acid production'],a:2,e:`Esophageal dysmotility in systemic sclerosis is caused primarily by fibrosis of smooth muscle and atrophy; the lower two-thirds of the oesophagus undergoes progressive collagen deposition replacing functional myocytes.<br><br>Loss of peristalsis and lower oesophageal sphincter tone produces dysphagia and severe gastro-oesophageal reflux. Proton pump inhibitors are essential. Strictures and Barrett oesophagus complicate long-standing reflux requiring surveillance.<br><br>Nerve compression at the C-spine (option A) is not the mechanism; Candida infection (option B) is a complication of immunosuppression rather than dysmotility cause; excessive acid production (option D) does not occur.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A 29-year-old woman with Raynaud’s phenomenon, puffy fingers, and muscle weakness has very high titers of Anti-U1 RNP. She does not meet full criteria for SLE or Scleroderma. What is the diagnosis?',o:['Mixed Connective Tissue Disease','Polymyalgia Rheumatica','Fibromyalgia','Rheumatoid Arthritis'],a:0,e:`Mixed connective tissue disease is the diagnosis; high-titre anti-U1 RNP antibody alongside Raynaud, puffy fingers, and myositis features without meeting criteria for SLE or scleroderma is characteristic.<br><br>MCTD shows features of SLE, systemic sclerosis, and polymyositis. Anti-U1 RNP produces a speckled ANA pattern. Pulmonary arterial hypertension is the leading cause of mortality, requiring screening.<br><br>Polymyalgia rheumatica (option B) affects older patients with shoulder/hip stiffness; fibromyalgia (option C) lacks autoantibodies and inflammation; rheumatoid arthritis (option D) has erosive symmetric polyarthritis with rheumatoid factor and anti-CCP positivity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a common hematologic abnormality in SLE?',o:['Thrombocytosis','Polycythemia','Elevated hemoglobin','Leukopenia'],a:3,e:`Leukopenia is a common haematologic abnormality in SLE; lymphopenia in particular is frequent and reflects autoimmune destruction, complement-mediated lysis, and bone marrow effects of active disease.<br><br>Other haematologic features include anaemia of chronic disease, autoimmune haemolytic anaemia (Coombs positive), and immune thrombocytopenia. Cytopenias contribute to one of the SLE classification criteria. Cyclophosphamide may further suppress counts.<br><br>Thrombocytosis (option A) is not characteristic, with thrombocytopenia being typical; polycythaemia (option B) does not occur; elevated haemoglobin (option C) is the opposite of the anaemia commonly seen in SLE patients.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Primary Sjogren’s syndrome occurs:',o:['In isolation, without another connective tissue disease','After a viral infection only','Only in the presence of Rheumatoid Arthritis','Only in males'],a:0,e:`Primary Sjogren syndrome occurs in isolation, without another connective tissue disease; secondary Sjogren occurs alongside another autoimmune condition such as rheumatoid arthritis, SLE, or systemic sclerosis.<br><br>Sjogren is characterised by destruction of exocrine glands by lymphocytic infiltrates, predominantly affecting females 40-60. Both forms present with sicca symptoms (dry eyes and mouth) and may show SS-A and SS-B antibodies.<br><br>Post-viral onset only (option B) is not specific; rheumatoid arthritis association (option C) describes secondary, not primary Sjogren; male-only occurrence (option D) is incorrect since the disease has marked female preponderance.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the most common cause of death in patients with Diffuse Systemic Sclerosis today?',o:['Scleroderma renal crisis','Stroke','Lung disease (Interstitial fibrosis or Pulmonary Hypertension)','Myocardial Infarction'],a:2,e:`Lung disease (interstitial fibrosis or pulmonary hypertension) is the most common cause of death in diffuse systemic sclerosis today; renal crisis mortality has fallen since ACE inhibitor introduction.<br><br>Pulmonary involvement combines interstitial fibrosis (mainly diffuse subtype with anti-Scl-70) and pulmonary arterial hypertension (mainly limited subtype). Annual screening with pulmonary function tests, HRCT, and echocardiography is essential.<br><br>Scleroderma renal crisis (option A) was historically leading but ACE inhibitors transformed prognosis; stroke (option B) is uncommon; myocardial infarction (option D) is not the leading cause despite coronary microvascular involvement.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient presents with painful oral ulcers and a butterfly rash. You suspect SLE. What is the most sensitive screening test?',o:['Anti-Smith','Anti-nuclear antibody (ANA)','Anti-dsDNA','ESR'],a:1,e:`Antinuclear antibody (ANA) is the most sensitive screening test for SLE; nearly all patients are ANA positive, making a negative ANA strong evidence against the diagnosis.<br><br>ANA is sensitive but not specific. Once positive, more specific tests such as anti-dsDNA and anti-Smith confirm SLE. ANA may also be positive in scleroderma, Sjogren, drug-induced lupus, and healthy individuals.<br><br>Anti-Smith (option A) is highly specific but not sensitive (only 30 percent positive), so cannot screen; anti-dsDNA (option C) is more specific than sensitive; ESR (option D) is non-specific inflammation marker without specificity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which medication is most likely to cause a drug-induced lupus-like syndrome?',o:['Metformin','Penicillin','Aspirin','Procainamide'],a:3,e:`Procainamide is the most likely cause of drug-induced lupus-like syndrome; this antiarrhythmic together with hydralazine carries the highest reported risk among offending agents.<br><br>Drug-induced lupus presents with arthralgia, serositis, and constitutional symptoms with positive ANA and anti-histone antibodies. Renal and CNS involvement is uncommon. Symptoms resolve after stopping the drug.<br><br>Metformin (option A) is not associated with drug-induced lupus; penicillin (option B) causes serum sickness and immediate hypersensitivity rather than lupus syndrome; aspirin (option C) does not produce lupus-like syndrome despite widespread use.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Neonatal lupus and congenital heart block are associated with the transfer of which maternal antibodies?',o:['Anti-Ro (SSA) and Anti-La (SSB)','Anti-dsDNA','Anti-U1 RNP','Anti-centromere'],a:0,e:`Anti-Ro (SSA) and Anti-La (SSB) maternal antibodies cross the placenta and cause neonatal lupus and congenital heart block; transplacental transfer damages the developing fetal cardiac conduction system.<br><br>Affected neonates develop transient cutaneous lupus rash and may have permanent congenital complete heart block requiring pacing. Mothers may have Sjogren, SLE, or be asymptomatic. Pregnancies require fetal echocardiographic surveillance.<br><br>Anti-dsDNA (option B) is associated with maternal lupus nephritis but not fetal heart block; anti-U1 RNP (option C) marks MCTD; anti-centromere (option D) is associated with limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis without neonatal cardiac risk.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Calcinosis cutis, seen in Scleroderma, involves:',o:['Iron deposits','Calcium deposits in the skin and subcutaneous tissues','Malignant bone growth','Soft tissue swelling'],a:1,e:`Calcinosis cutis in scleroderma involves calcium deposits in the skin and subcutaneous tissues; insoluble calcium hydroxyapatite accumulates in periarticular soft tissue, particularly fingers, forearms, and pressure points.<br><br>Lesions appear as firm white nodules that may ulcerate and extrude chalky material. Calcinosis is a component of CREST syndrome (limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis). No effective medical therapy exists.<br><br>Iron deposits (option A) characterise haemochromatosis with bronze pigmentation rather than scleroderma; malignant bone growth (option C) is unrelated; soft tissue swelling alone (option D) understates the discrete calcified deposits seen radiographically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with Serum Sickness typically shows which profile on laboratory testing?',o:['Negative ESR','High complement levels','Low complement levels (C3, C4)','Positive ANA'],a:2,e:`Serum sickness typically shows low complement levels (C3 and C4); circulating immune complexes activate and consume the classical complement pathway, producing measurable hypocomplementaemia during the acute phase.<br><br>Mechanism is type III hypersensitivity. Other findings include leukocytosis, raised ESR, and sometimes proteinuria from immune complex glomerulonephritis. Symptoms appear 7-14 days after antigen exposure and resolve as antigen clears.<br><br>Negative ESR (option A) is not seen in this inflammatory state; high complement levels (option B) are the opposite of consumption-driven hypocomplementaemia; positive ANA (option D) characterises SLE rather than serum sickness.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is NOT a common manifestation of SLE?',o:['Oral ulcers','High-impact fractures','Non-erosive arthritis','Photosensitivity'],a:1,e:`High-impact fractures are not a common manifestation of SLE; fragility fractures may occur from steroid-induced osteoporosis with chronic therapy, but acute high-impact fractures are not part of disease pathology.<br><br>Common SLE manifestations follow the RASH OR PAIN mnemonic: Rash, Arthritis (nonerosive), Serositis, Hematologic disorders, Oral ulcers, Renal disease, Photosensitivity, ANA, Immunologic, Neurologic disorders.<br><br>Oral ulcers (option A) feature in SLE classification criteria; non-erosive arthritis (option C) is characteristic and listed in classification criteria; photosensitivity (option D) is among the cutaneous criteria for SLE diagnosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The "gold standard" for identifying Raynaud’s phenomenon involves:',o:['Skin biopsy','Nerve conduction study','Hand X-ray','Clinical history of color changes (white-blue-red)'],a:3,e:`Clinical history of color changes (white-blue-red) is the gold standard for identifying Raynaud phenomenon; the triphasic pallor-cyanosis-rubor sequence on cold or stress provocation establishes the diagnosis.<br><br>Pallor reflects ischaemic vasospasm, cyanosis reflects deoxygenation in stagnant blood, and rubor reflects reactive hyperaemia on rewarming. Most often in fingers and toes. Secondary Raynaud may show digital ulceration.<br><br>Skin biopsy (option A) is not used; nerve conduction (option B) tests neuropathy rather than vasospasm; hand X-ray (option C) does not visualise vasomotor changes and would only show calcinosis or terminal phalangeal resorption.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a life-threatening complication of SLE that requires immediate immunosuppression?',o:['Symmetrical arthralgia','Alopecia','Diffuse Proliferative Glomerulonephritis','Malar rash'],a:2,e:`Diffuse proliferative glomerulonephritis is a life-threatening SLE complication requiring immediate immunosuppression; Class IV lupus nephritis carries highest renal failure risk and warrants aggressive cyclophosphamide or mycophenolate induction.<br><br>Lupus nephritis arises from glomerular deposition of anti-DNA immune complexes producing nephritic or nephrotic syndromes. Renal biopsy guides treatment intensity. Untreated disease progresses rapidly to end-stage renal disease.<br><br>Symmetrical arthralgia (option A) is non-erosive and symptomatically managed; alopecia (option B) reflects active disease but is not life-threatening; malar rash (option D) is a classification criterion treated with hydroxychloroquine.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'In Sjogren’s syndrome, the Schirmer test measures:',o:['Tear production','Sweat production','Gastric acid','Saliva production'],a:0,e:`The Schirmer test in Sjogren syndrome measures tear production; filter paper strips placed in the lower conjunctival fornix wet less than 5 mm in 5 minutes.<br><br>Reduced tear production from autoimmune lacrimal gland destruction produces gritty eye sensation and corneal damage. Schirmer testing supports the diagnosis alongside ocular staining tests with rose bengal or lissamine green.<br><br>Sweat production (option B) is unrelated to Sjogren glandular involvement; gastric acid (option C) is measured by pH testing; saliva production (option D) is assessed by sialometry, a separate test for the oral component.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Digital pitting scars and loss of finger pulp are characteristic of:',o:['Serum Sickness','Sjogren’s Syndrome','Systemic Sclerosis','SLE'],a:2,e:`Digital pitting scars and loss of finger pulp are characteristic of systemic sclerosis; severe Raynaud-induced ischaemia produces small infarcts on fingertips that heal as pitted scars.<br><br>Critical digital ischaemia in secondary Raynaud syndrome leads to ulceration, autoamputation in extreme cases, and the typical pitted appearance. Scleroderma sclerodactyly tightens the fingertip skin progressively, contributing to the appearance.<br><br>Serum sickness (option A) is acute and resolves without scarring; Sjogren syndrome (option B) features sicca rather than digital ischaemia; SLE (option D) may produce Raynaud but rarely the severe digital scarring of established sclerosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibody is most associated with Diffuse Systemic Sclerosis and a higher risk of interstitial lung disease?',o:['Anti-Scl-70 (Topoisomerase I)','Anti-Smith','Anti-centromere','Rheumatoid Factor'],a:0,e:`Anti-Scl-70 (Topoisomerase I) is most associated with diffuse systemic sclerosis and predicts higher risk of interstitial lung disease; the antibody marks aggressive widespread disease with early visceral involvement.<br><br>Diffuse scleroderma shows widespread skin involvement, rapid progression, and early visceral involvement. Anti-Scl-70 positivity warrants annual pulmonary function testing and high-resolution CT screening for interstitial lung disease.<br><br>Anti-Smith (option B) is highly specific for SLE rather than scleroderma; anti-centromere (option C) is associated with limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis (CREST); rheumatoid factor (option D) characterises rheumatoid arthritis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with SLE presents with sudden onset shortness of breath and pleuritic pain. CT scan shows a pulmonary embolism. Which test should be prioritized?',o:['Anti-histone','Antiphospholipid antibodies','Serum calcium','HLA-B27'],a:1,e:`Antiphospholipid antibodies should be prioritised; SLE patients with sudden pulmonary embolism warrant testing for lupus anticoagulant, anticardiolipin, and anti-beta2 glycoprotein antibodies given high prevalence of secondary antiphospholipid syndrome.<br><br>Antiphospholipid syndrome is a primary or secondary autoimmune disorder, most commonly associated with SLE. Diagnose based on history of thrombosis or spontaneous abortion plus laboratory antiphospholipid antibodies. Treat with anticoagulation.<br><br>Anti-histone (option A) marks drug-induced lupus and does not predict thrombosis; serum calcium (option C) is irrelevant to embolic disease; HLA-B27 (option D) is associated with seronegative spondyloarthropathies, not antiphospholipid thrombosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Management of Raynaud\'s phenomenon in Scleroderma first involves:',o:['High dose Prednisone','Anticoagulation with Warfarin','Amputation','Keeping hands warm and Calcium Channel Blockers (e.g., Nifedipine)'],a:3,e:`Initial Raynaud management in scleroderma involves keeping hands warm and calcium channel blockers (eg, nifedipine); these dihydropyridines are first-line vasodilators for primary and secondary Raynaud phenomenon.<br><br>Treat Raynaud with calcium channel blockers (smaller-vessel vasospasm responds to dihydropyridines). Lifestyle measures include warm clothing, gloves, smoking cessation, and avoiding cold exposure. Severe digital ulceration may require iloprost.<br><br>High-dose prednisone (option A) precipitates renal crisis and is contraindicated; warfarin anticoagulation (option B) does not address vasospasm; amputation (option C) is the last resort for irreversible critical ischaemia, not initial management.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Serum sickness-like reaction can be caused by which common pediatric antibiotic?',o:['Erythromycin','Cefaclor','Amoxicillin','Gentamicin'],a:1,e:`Cefaclor is a common pediatric antibiotic causing serum sickness-like reactions; the second-generation cephalosporin produces characteristic fever, urticarial rash, and arthralgia about 7-14 days after initiation.<br><br>Mechanism is thought to involve drug metabolites rather than classical immune complex deposition. Reaction typically resolves spontaneously after discontinuation. Pediatric clinicians should counsel families about this distinctive complication when prescribing cefaclor.<br><br>Erythromycin (option A) is associated with cholestatic hepatitis but not classical serum sickness; amoxicillin (option C) causes hypersensitivity and rash but cefaclor is the more notable offender; gentamicin (option D) causes nephrotoxicity instead.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Chronic Discoid Lupus erythematosus primarily affects the:',o:['Lungs','Brain','Skin','Kidneys'],a:2,e:`Chronic discoid lupus erythematosus primarily affects the skin; well-demarcated erythematous plaques with adherent scale, follicular plugging, and atrophic scarring localise to face, scalp, and ears.<br><br>Discoid lupus may occur in isolation or as a cutaneous manifestation of systemic lupus erythematosus. Photosensitivity is prominent. Biopsy shows interface dermatitis. Treatment includes topical steroids, hydroxychloroquine, and strict photoprotection.<br><br>Lungs (option A), brain (option B), and kidneys (option D) may be affected in systemic lupus but are not features of chronic discoid lupus erythematosus, which is by definition a localised cutaneous disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the classic finding on nailfold capillarioscopy in a patient with Systemic Sclerosis?',o:['Dilated "giant" capillary loops and dropout areas','Normal capillary loops','Fungal infection','Absence of capillaries'],a:0,e:`Dilated giant capillary loops and dropout areas are the classic nailfold capillaroscopy finding in systemic sclerosis; abnormal capillary architecture distinguishes secondary Raynaud from primary Raynaud disease.<br><br>Capillaroscopy uses dermatoscopy or specialised microscopy to visualise nailfold capillaries. Scleroderma pattern shows enlarged loops, capillary dropout, and microhaemorrhages. The findings predict progression and help differentiate secondary from primary Raynaud.<br><br>Normal capillary loops (option B) define primary Raynaud rather than scleroderma; fungal infection (option C) is unrelated; absence of capillaries (option D) is too extreme and does not describe the dropout pattern with surviving giant loops.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A 40-year-old female with MCTD develops severe muscle weakness and an elevated Creatine Kinase (CK). This component of MCTD mimics:',o:['SLE','Rheumatoid Arthritis','Scleroderma','Polymyositis'],a:3,e:`Severe muscle weakness with elevated creatine kinase in MCTD mimics polymyositis; one of the three overlap diseases comprising MCTD is polymyositis alongside SLE and systemic sclerosis features.<br><br>Polymyositis shows progressive symmetric proximal muscle weakness with endomysial inflammation and CD8 T-cell infiltrate. Treatment includes steroids and methotrexate. MCTD myositis component responds similarly.<br><br>SLE (option A) features arthralgia and rash without elevated CK; rheumatoid arthritis (option B) is symmetric polyarthritis without myositis; scleroderma (option C) involves skin fibrosis and visceral disease but myositis is not its defining feature.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hydroxychloroquine therapy in SLE requires regular screening of which organ due to potential toxicity?',o:['Ears','Eyes (Retina)','Liver','Kidneys'],a:1,e:`Hydroxychloroquine therapy in SLE requires regular screening of the eyes (retina); cumulative drug exposure can produce irreversible bull's-eye maculopathy with central visual loss.<br><br>Annual ophthalmologic screening with optical coherence tomography and visual field testing is recommended after five years or earlier in patients with high cumulative dose, kidney disease, or pre-existing maculopathy.<br><br>Ears (option A) are not a target of hydroxychloroquine toxicity; liver (option C) is not the primary screening site; kidneys (option D) require monitoring for lupus nephritis itself rather than for hydroxychloroquine toxicity, which is retinal.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'In Sjogren’s Syndrome, the presence of Anti-Ro/SSA antibodies in a pregnant woman is a risk for:',o:['Maternal liver failure','Maternal hypertension','Fetal congenital heart block','Fetal macrosomia'],a:2,e:`Anti-Ro/SSA antibodies in a pregnant Sjogren patient pose risk of fetal congenital heart block; transplacental antibody transfer damages the developing cardiac conduction system in the second trimester.<br><br>Affected fetuses develop varying degrees of atrioventricular block, often complete and permanent, requiring postnatal pacing. Fetal echocardiographic surveillance from 16 weeks detects bradycardia early. Hydroxychloroquine in pregnancy may reduce risk.<br><br>Maternal liver failure (option A) is not associated; maternal hypertension (option B) is not antibody-mediated; fetal macrosomia (option D) relates to maternal diabetes rather than autoantibody transfer, with no link to anti-Ro positivity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'"Mouselike" facies (pinched nose, small mouth) is a clinical description of a patient with:',o:['Systemic Sclerosis','Sjogren’s Syndrome','Mixed Connective Tissue Disease','SLE'],a:0,e:`Mouselike facies (pinched nose, small mouth) describes a patient with systemic sclerosis; progressive skin fibrosis tightens facial skin around the nose and mouth, producing the distinctive constricted appearance.<br><br>Other facial features include radial perioral furrowing, microstomia limiting mouth opening, telangiectasias, and pinched nose. Sclerodactyly affects the hands. Calcinosis cutis may develop. Limited form is associated with anti-centromere antibody.<br><br>Sjogren syndrome (option B) produces xerostomia and xerophthalmia without skin tightening; mixed connective tissue disease (option C) shares some features but lacks classical sclerodermatous facies; SLE (option D) features malar rash instead.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following differentiates SLE from Scleroderma?',o:['SLE is an autoimmune disease; Scleroderma is not','SLE often has erosive arthritis; Scleroderma does not','Scleroderma has positive ANA; SLE does not','SLE has a characteristic malar rash; Scleroderma has skin tightening/fibrosis'],a:3,e:`Malar rash characterises SLE while skin tightening and fibrosis characterise scleroderma; these distinct cutaneous features reliably differentiate the two connective tissue diseases on clinical examination.<br><br>SLE skin involvement includes malar (butterfly) rash sparing nasolabial folds, discoid lesions, and photosensitivity. Scleroderma produces sclerodactyly, mouselike facies, calcinosis cutis, and digital ischaemic changes. Histology and serology further distinguish.<br><br>Both are autoimmune (option A is wrong); SLE arthritis is non-erosive (option B reverses correct picture); both have positive ANA (option C contradicts standard serology), so only the cutaneous distinction in option D is reliable.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 22-year-old male presents with chronic low back pain that is worst in the morning and improves with exercise. He also reports occasional redness and pain in his right eye. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Lumbar disc herniation','Behcet’s syndrome','Ankylosing spondylitis','Polyarteritis nodosa'],a:2,e:`Ankylosing spondylitis is the most likely diagnosis; chronic inflammatory back pain worse in the morning, improving with exercise, in a young man with concomitant uveitis points to axial spondyloarthritis.<br><br>Seronegative spondyloarthritis lacks rheumatoid factor and shows strong HLA-B27 association. Subtypes share inflammatory back pain (with morning stiffness, improves with exercise), peripheral arthritis, enthesitis, dactylitis, and uveitis.<br><br>Lumbar disc herniation (option A) produces mechanical pain worse on movement, not improving with exercise; Behcet syndrome (option B) features oral and genital ulcers; polyarteritis nodosa (option D) is a vasculitis without inflammatory back pain.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which genetic marker is present in approximately 90% of white patients with Ankylosing Spondylitis?',o:['HLA-B27','HLA-DR4','HLA-B51','HLA-DQ8'],a:0,e:`HLA-B27 is present in approximately 90 percent of white patients with ankylosing spondylitis; this MHC class I serotype is the strongest genetic association in seronegative spondyloarthritis pathogenesis.<br><br>Seronegative spondyloarthritis lacks rheumatoid factor with strong HLA-B27 association. Other PAIR subtypes (psoriatic, ankylosing, IBD-associated, reactive) share variable HLA-B27 frequency. Population frequency of B27 is roughly 8 percent.<br><br>HLA-DR4 (option B) is associated with rheumatoid arthritis and type 1 diabetes; HLA-B51 (option C) is the major association of Behcet syndrome; HLA-DQ8 (option D) is linked with celiac disease and not ankylosing spondylitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 30-year-old male with recurring painful oral ulcers, genital ulcers, and uveitis undergoes a skin prick test that results in a sterile pustule 48 hours later. What is this positive sign called?',o:['Koebner phenomenon','Nikolsky sign','Auspitz sign','Pathergy test'],a:3,e:`The pathergy test is the positive sign described; a sterile pustule developing 24-48 hours after needle prick in a Behcet patient reflects exaggerated cutaneous response to minor trauma.<br><br>Pathergy is included in diagnostic criteria for Behcet syndrome alongside oral ulcers, genital ulcers, eye lesions (uveitis), and skin lesions. Higher positivity occurs in Mediterranean and Middle Eastern populations.<br><br>Koebner phenomenon (option A) describes lesions appearing along scratch lines in psoriasis or lichen planus; Nikolsky sign (option B) is epidermal sliding in pemphigus; Auspitz sign (option C) is pinpoint bleeding after psoriatic scale removal.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the classic radiographic finding in the spine of a patient with advanced Ankylosing Spondylitis?',o:['Codfish vertebrae','Bamboo spine','Osteoblastic lesions','Wedge fractures'],a:1,e:`Bamboo spine is the classic radiographic finding in advanced ankylosing spondylitis; vertebral fusion (ankylosis) through ossification of the annulus fibrosus and ligaments produces the characteristic continuous bony column.<br><br>Ankylosing spondylitis features symmetric involvement of spine and sacroiliac joints leading to ankylosis (joint fusion), uveitis, and aortic regurgitation. Bamboo spine is a hallmark of advanced disease, more common in males.<br><br>Codfish vertebrae (option A) describes biconcave deformity in osteoporosis or osteomalacia; osteoblastic lesions (option C) suggest metastases or Paget disease; wedge fractures (option D) are osteoporotic compression fractures, distinct from diffuse fusion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 45-year-old male presents with abdominal pain, weight loss, and new-onset hypertension. He has livedo reticularis on his legs and tested positive for Hepatitis B. Which vasculitis should be suspected?',o:['Polyarteritis nodosa (PAN)','Giant cell arteritis','Granulomatosis with polyangiitis','Takayasu arteritis'],a:0,e:`Polyarteritis nodosa should be suspected; the combination of abdominal pain, weight loss, hypertension, livedo reticularis, and hepatitis B positivity is highly characteristic of this medium-vessel vasculitis.<br><br>PAN typically involves renal and visceral vessels, not pulmonary arteries. Hepatitis B seropositivity occurs in 30 percent. Features include fever, weight loss, malaise, abdominal pain, melena, hypertension, neurologic dysfunction, and renal damage.<br><br>Giant cell arteritis (option B) affects elderly with headache and jaw claudication; granulomatosis with polyangiitis (option C) involves upper respiratory tract and kidneys with c-ANCA; Takayasu arteritis (option D) affects the aortic arch.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Anaphylactoid purpura, also known as Henoch-Schönlein purpura (HSP), is characterized by the deposition of which immune complex?',o:['IgM','IgA','IgG','IgE'],a:1,e:`Henoch-Schonlein purpura is characterised by IgA immune complex deposition; vasculitis secondary to IgA immune complex deposition produces palpable purpura, arthralgia, and abdominal pain in children.<br><br>HSP is the most common childhood systemic vasculitis and often follows upper respiratory infection. Classic triad: skin (palpable purpura on buttocks/legs), arthralgias, GI (abdominal pain). Associated with IgA nephropathy.<br><br>IgM (option A) is not the predominant immunoglobulin; IgG (option C) is involved in serum sickness type III hypersensitivity but not HSP; IgE (option D) mediates type I immediate hypersensitivity reactions, not IgA immune complex disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 6-year-old boy presents with palpable purpura on his buttocks and lower legs, abdominal pain, and joint swelling. His renal biopsy shows mesangial IgA deposits. What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Microscopic polyangiitis','Kawasaki disease','Anaphylactoid purpura','Polyarteritis nodosa'],a:2,e:`Anaphylactoid purpura (Henoch-Schonlein purpura) is the most likely diagnosis; the classical pediatric tetrad of palpable purpura, arthralgia, abdominal pain, and IgA nephropathy on biopsy confirms the disease.<br><br>HSP is the most common childhood systemic vasculitis and often follows upper respiratory tract infection. Mesangial IgA deposits on renal biopsy mirror IgA nephropathy. Most cases are self-limiting; renal involvement determines prognosis.<br><br>Microscopic polyangiitis (option A) shows pauci-immune glomerulonephritis with MPO-ANCA, not IgA deposits; Kawasaki disease (option B) features mucocutaneous rash and coronary aneurysms; polyarteritis nodosa (option D) lacks IgA deposits.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a major complication of Polyarteritis Nodosa involving the renal system?',o:['Glomerulonephritis','Renal cell carcinoma','Nephrotic syndrome','Renal artery aneurysms and ischemia'],a:3,e:`Renal artery aneurysms and ischaemia represent a major polyarteritis nodosa complication; transmural inflammation of medium-sized arteries weakens vessel walls producing innumerable microaneurysms visible on arteriography.<br><br>PAN involves renal and visceral vessels with immune complex-mediated transmural inflammation and fibrinoid necrosis. Different stages of inflammation may coexist in different vessels. Innumerable renal microaneurysms and spasms appear on arteriogram.<br><br>Glomerulonephritis (option A) is a small-vessel vasculitis feature, not classical PAN; renal cell carcinoma (option B) is unrelated; nephrotic syndrome (option C) reflects glomerular podocyte disease, distinct from medium-vessel arterial inflammation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Behcet\'s syndrome, what is the most common cause of morbidity and potential blindness?',o:['Recurrent genital ulcers','Posterior uveitis or retinal vasculitis','Erythema nodosum','Oral ulcers'],a:1,e:`Posterior uveitis or retinal vasculitis is the most common cause of morbidity and potential blindness in Behcet syndrome; sight-threatening intraocular inflammation requires urgent immunosuppressive therapy.<br><br>Behcet causes recurrent oral ulcers, genital ulcers, uveitis, and skin lesions. Posterior segment involvement carries highest visual risk. Treatment includes corticosteroids and steroid-sparing agents such as azathioprine, cyclosporine, or anti-TNF biologics.<br><br>Recurrent genital ulcers (option A) are painful but not blinding; erythema nodosum (option C) is a tender skin lesion without visual implications; oral ulcers (option D) are most common but mucocutaneous rather than sight-threatening like uveitis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is considered first-line pharmacological management for Ankylosing Spondylitis?',o:['NSAIDs','Hydroxychloroquine','Methotrexate','Oral corticosteroids'],a:0,e:`NSAIDs are first-line pharmacological management for ankylosing spondylitis; they reduce inflammation, pain, and stiffness, with continuous use possibly slowing radiographic progression in some studies.<br><br>If NSAIDs fail, anti-TNF biologics (etanercept, adalimumab, infliximab) are next-line therapy. Conventional DMARDs are ineffective for axial disease. Physiotherapy with daily exercise is essential alongside pharmacotherapy for outcomes.<br><br>Hydroxychloroquine (option B) is used in SLE; methotrexate (option C) is effective for peripheral but not axial disease in ankylosing spondylitis; oral corticosteroids (option D) are not first-line for axial spondyloarthritis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A 35-year-old woman presents with claudication of the arms and an absent radial pulse on the left side. Imaging shows narrowing of the aortic arch. What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Polyarteritis nodosa','Ankylosing spondylitis','Behcet\'s syndrome','Takayasu arteritis'],a:3,e:`Takayasu arteritis is the diagnosis; usually Asian females under 40 with pulseless disease (weak upper extremity pulses), fever, night sweats, arthritis, and ocular disturbances point to this large-vessel vasculitis.<br><br>Granulomatous thickening and narrowing of the aortic arch and proximal great vessels reduces upper limb perfusion. ESR is elevated. Treat with corticosteroids; biologics may be added in refractory disease.<br><br>Polyarteritis nodosa (option A) involves medium vessels not the aortic arch; ankylosing spondylitis (option B) is a spondyloarthropathy not vasculitis; Behcet syndrome (option C) features mucocutaneous ulcers and uveitis without pulseless disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The "Schober test" is used in physical examination to measure the mobility of which area?',o:['Shoulder joint','Sacroiliac joint','Lumbar spine','Cervical spine'],a:2,e:`The Schober test measures lumbar spine mobility; reduced forward flexion of the lumbar spine indicates restriction characteristic of axial spondyloarthritis, particularly ankylosing spondylitis.<br><br>Marks placed at the L5 spinous process and 10 cm above should separate to over 15 cm on full forward flexion. Less than 5 cm increase suggests significant restriction supporting modified New York criteria for ankylosing spondylitis.<br><br>Shoulder joint (option A) is assessed by range-of-motion and impingement tests; sacroiliac joint (option B) is assessed by FABER and Gaenslen manoeuvres; cervical spine (option D) uses occiput-to-wall and tragus-to-wall measurements.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Polyarteritis nodosa (PAN) characteristically spares which organ system?',o:['Lungs','Skin','Kidneys','Gastrointestinal tract'],a:0,e:`Polyarteritis nodosa characteristically spares the lungs; it typically involves renal and visceral vessels but does not affect pulmonary arteries, distinguishing it from ANCA-associated vasculitides.<br><br>PAN involves transmural inflammation of medium-sized arteries with fibrinoid necrosis. Different stages of inflammation may coexist in different vessels. The pulmonary sparing helps differentiate PAN from granulomatosis with polyangiitis and microscopic polyangiitis.<br><br>Skin (option B) is commonly involved with livedo reticularis and nodules; kidneys (option C) are major targets with renal artery aneurysms and ischaemia; gastrointestinal tract (option D) shows abdominal pain and melena from mesenteric vessel involvement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the most common extra-articular manifestation of Ankylosing Spondylitis?',o:['Aortic regurgitation','Amyloidosis','Pulmonary fibrosis','Acute anterior uveitis'],a:3,e:`Acute anterior uveitis is the most common extra-articular manifestation of ankylosing spondylitis; recurrent painful red eye with photophobia occurs in up to 40 percent of patients.<br><br>Ankylosing spondylitis features symmetric involvement of spine and sacroiliac joints leading to ankylosis (joint fusion), uveitis, and aortic regurgitation. Bamboo spine is the radiographic hallmark of advanced disease.<br><br>Aortic regurgitation (option A) occurs but is less common than uveitis; amyloidosis (option B) is a rare late complication; pulmonary fibrosis (option C) can develop as upper-lobe apical fibrobullous disease but is much less frequent.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with Behcet’s syndrome presents with sudden calf pain and swelling. Which vascular complication are they at high risk for?',o:['Aortic dissection','Venous thrombosis','Coronary artery disease','Raynaud’s phenomenon'],a:1,e:`Venous thrombosis is the high-risk vascular complication; Behcet syndrome predisposes to deep vein thrombosis, superficial thrombophlebitis, and dural sinus thrombosis through inflammatory endothelial injury.<br><br>Vascular Behcet involves both venous (more common) and arterial systems. Pulmonary artery aneurysms carry high mortality risk. Anticoagulation is controversial when concurrent pulmonary aneurysms exist; immunosuppression is the cornerstone of vascular disease management.<br><br>Aortic dissection (option A) is uncommon; coronary artery disease (option C) is not a typical Behcet complication; Raynaud phenomenon (option D) is associated with connective tissue diseases like scleroderma rather than Behcet syndrome's vascular pattern.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Large-vessel vasculitis includes which of the following conditions?',o:['Wegener’s granulomatosis','Polyarteritis nodosa','Giant cell arteritis','Churg-Strauss syndrome'],a:2,e:`Giant cell arteritis is a large-vessel vasculitis; it most commonly affects branches of the carotid artery in elderly females, presenting with unilateral headache and jaw claudication.<br><br>Focal granulomatous inflammation of the temporal artery underlies the disease. ESR is typically markedly elevated. Treat with high-dose corticosteroids prior to temporal artery biopsy to prevent ophthalmic artery occlusion and irreversible blindness.<br><br>Wegener granulomatosis (option A) is a small-vessel vasculitis with c-ANCA positivity; polyarteritis nodosa (option B) is a medium-vessel vasculitis; Churg-Strauss syndrome (option D) is a small-vessel vasculitis with eosinophilia and asthma.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 50-year-old male with Polyarteritis Nodosa presents with "foot drop." This is likely due to:',o:['Mononeuritis multiplex','Muscle atrophy from disuse','Central nervous system stroke','Spinal stenosis'],a:0,e:`Foot drop in polyarteritis nodosa results from mononeuritis multiplex; vasculitic occlusion of the vasa nervorum produces ischaemic injury to peripheral nerves in random distribution.<br><br>Common peroneal nerve involvement causes foot drop. Other affected nerves include median, ulnar, and radial. Mononeuritis multiplex is a hallmark of vasculitic neuropathy and may also occur in granulomatosis with polyangiitis.<br><br>Muscle atrophy from disuse (option B) does not produce the asymmetric pattern; CNS stroke (option C) would localise to specific cerebral territories; spinal stenosis (option D) produces bilateral lower limb symptoms with neurogenic claudication.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a classic clinical triad for Anaphylactoid purpura (HSP)?',o:['Oral ulcers, genital ulcers, and uveitis','Fever, weight loss, and anemia','Purpura, abdominal pain, and arthritis','Hemoptysis, hematuria, and sinusitis'],a:2,e:`Henoch-Schonlein purpura classic triad is purpura, abdominal pain, and arthritis; cutaneous palpable purpura on buttocks and legs accompanies arthralgia and gastrointestinal involvement.<br><br>HSP is the most common childhood systemic vasculitis and often follows upper respiratory tract infection. Vasculitis is secondary to IgA immune complex deposition. Associated with IgA nephropathy (Berger disease) on renal biopsy.<br><br>Oral, genital ulcers and uveitis (option A) define Behcet syndrome; fever, weight loss, anaemia (option B) are non-specific; haemoptysis, haematuria, sinusitis (option D) describe the upper-lower-renal triad of granulomatosis with polyangiitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the typical "gold standard" for diagnosing Polyarteritis Nodosa?',o:['Chest X-ray','Skin prick test','ANA and RF testing','Tissue biopsy or visceral angiography'],a:3,e:`Tissue biopsy or visceral angiography is the gold standard for polyarteritis nodosa; biopsy shows transmural inflammation with fibrinoid necrosis, while angiography reveals microaneurysms and stenoses.<br><br>Innumerable renal microaneurysms and spasms appear on arteriogram. Biopsy of skin, sural nerve, or symptomatic muscle confirms vasculitis. Different stages of inflammation may coexist in different vessels supporting the histology.<br><br>Chest X-ray (option A) is unrevealing since PAN spares the lungs; skin prick test (option B) is for allergic disorders not vasculitis; ANA and RF (option C) are negative in PAN, distinguishing it from connective tissue diseases.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Ankylosing Spondylitis belongs to a group of diseases known as:',o:['Connective tissue diseases','Seronegative spondyloarthropathies','Crystal-induced arthropathies','Systemic vasculitides'],a:1,e:`Ankylosing spondylitis belongs to the seronegative spondyloarthropathies; this group includes psoriatic, ankylosing, IBD-associated, and reactive arthritis, sharing HLA-B27 association and absence of rheumatoid factor.<br><br>Subtypes (PAIR) share variable occurrence of inflammatory back pain (associated with morning stiffness, improves with exercise), peripheral arthritis, enthesitis, dactylitis (sausage fingers), and uveitis. Strong association with HLA-B27 (MHC class I serotype).<br><br>Connective tissue diseases (option A) include SLE, scleroderma, and dermatomyositis with autoantibodies; crystal-induced arthropathies (option C) include gout and pseudogout; systemic vasculitides (option D) involve blood vessel inflammation, distinct entities entirely.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Behcet’s syndrome, the HLA association most commonly cited is:',o:['HLA-DQ2','HLA-B27','HLA-B51','HLA-DR4'],a:2,e:`HLA-B51 is the major HLA association of Behcet syndrome; this MHC class I serotype is most prevalent in Mediterranean and East Asian populations along the historical Silk Road.<br><br>Behcet causes recurrent oral ulcers, genital ulcers, uveitis, and skin lesions. Pathergy test (sterile pustule after needle prick) is included in diagnostic criteria. Higher disease prevalence parallels HLA-B51 frequency.<br><br>HLA-DQ2 (option A) is associated with celiac disease; HLA-B27 (option B) is associated with ankylosing spondylitis and other seronegative spondyloarthropathies; HLA-DR4 (option D) is associated with rheumatoid arthritis and type 1 diabetes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a common gastrointestinal complication of Anaphylactoid purpura?',o:['Intussusception','Primary biliary cirrhosis','Cholecystitis','Gastric cancer'],a:0,e:`Intussusception is a common gastrointestinal complication of HSP; bowel wall oedema and haemorrhage from IgA-mediated vasculitis trigger ileoileal intussusception, atypical for the usual ileocolic site.<br><br>Abdominal pain in HSP may be severe and colicky. Ultrasound is the imaging of choice for diagnosis. Most cases reduce spontaneously or non-operatively. Surgical intervention is reserved for irreducible intussusception or bowel infarction.<br><br>Primary biliary cirrhosis (option B) is an autoimmune cholangiopathy unrelated to HSP; cholecystitis (option C) is not a recognised HSP complication; gastric cancer (option D) has no association with childhood IgA vasculitis at all.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The "string of beads" appearance on angiography is characteristic of:',o:['Takayasu arteritis','Polyarteritis nodosa','Temporal arteritis','Granulomatosis with polyangiitis'],a:1,e:`String of beads appearance on angiography is characteristic of polyarteritis nodosa; alternating dilations (microaneurysms) and stenoses give the classical beaded pattern in renal and visceral arteries.<br><br>Innumerable renal microaneurysms and spasms on arteriogram support the diagnosis. The pattern reflects transmural inflammation with fibrinoid necrosis at different stages in different vessels. CT angiography demonstrates the lesions characteristically.<br><br>Takayasu arteritis (option A) shows long-segment narrowing of aortic arch and great vessels; temporal arteritis (option C) does not produce angiographic beading; granulomatosis with polyangiitis (option D) shows lung cavities, not vascular beading.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which joint is typically the first to show changes on X-ray in Ankylosing Spondylitis?',o:['Distal interphalangeal joint','Knee joint','Shoulder joint','Sacroiliac joint'],a:3,e:`Sacroiliac joint is the first to show radiographic changes in ankylosing spondylitis; bilateral symmetric sacroiliitis is the earliest and most reliable plain film finding in axial spondyloarthritis.<br><br>Symmetric involvement of spine and sacroiliac joints leads to ankylosis (joint fusion). Modified New York criteria require radiographic sacroiliitis. MRI detects active inflammation before plain film changes appear.<br><br>Distal interphalangeal joint (option A) is affected in psoriatic arthritis and osteoarthritis; knee joint (option B) is not a primary AS site; shoulder joint (option C) may be involved later but not as the initial radiographic site.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Behcet’s syndrome is most prevalent in populations from which geographic region?',o:['North America','Sub-Saharan Africa','"Silk Road" (Mediterranean to East Asia)','Northern Europe'],a:2,e:`Behcet syndrome is most prevalent along the Silk Road from the Mediterranean to East Asia; Turkey, Iran, China, Japan, and Korea show highest prevalence corresponding to HLA-B51 distribution.<br><br>The geographic gradient parallels HLA-B51 frequency. Disease tends to be more severe in male patients of Middle Eastern and East Asian descent. Younger age at onset and ocular involvement are also more common.<br><br>North America (option A) has low prevalence; Sub-Saharan Africa (option B) has very low rates; Northern Europe (option D) is similarly low-prevalence, contrasting sharply with the Silk Road distribution of Behcet.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which medication is often used specifically for the management of oral and genital ulcers in Behcet\'s?',o:['Colchicine','Vitamin B12','Warfarin','Penicillin'],a:0,e:`Colchicine is used for management of oral and genital ulcers in Behcet syndrome; it reduces frequency and severity of mucocutaneous lesions through neutrophil chemotaxis inhibition.<br><br>Colchicine is also useful for erythema nodosum and arthritis components. More severe disease (uveitis, vascular, neurological) requires corticosteroids and immunosuppressants such as azathioprine or anti-TNF biologics. Apremilast is an oral PDE4 inhibitor option for refractory ulcers.<br><br>Vitamin B12 (option B) treats megaloblastic anaemia; warfarin (option C) is anticoagulation; penicillin (option D) treats bacterial infection but has no role in autoimmune mucocutaneous disease management in Behcet syndrome.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A 60-year-old male presents with headache, jaw claudication, and a thickened, tender temporal artery. What is the most feared complication?',o:['Tooth loss','Hearing loss','Renal failure','Permanent blindness'],a:3,e:`Permanent blindness is the most feared complication of giant cell (temporal) arteritis; ophthalmic artery occlusion produces irreversible ischaemic optic neuropathy without prompt corticosteroid treatment.<br><br>Treat with high-dose corticosteroids prior to temporal artery biopsy to prevent blindness. Bilateral involvement is feared because second eye loss can follow within days. ESR aids urgent decision-making.<br><br>Tooth loss (option A) is not a recognised complication; hearing loss (option B) is not a typical GCA feature though may occur in granulomatosis with polyangiitis; renal failure (option C) is not characteristic of giant cell arteritis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the primary histological feature of Polyarteritis Nodosa?',o:['Granulomatous inflammation','Necrotizing inflammation of medium-sized arteries','IgA deposition in capillaries','Giant cells in the media'],a:1,e:`Necrotizing inflammation of medium-sized arteries is the primary histological feature of polyarteritis nodosa; transmural inflammation with fibrinoid necrosis defines the disease pathologically.<br><br>Different stages of inflammation may coexist in different vessels. Immune complex mediation drives the lesions. Neutrophilic infiltrate in acute phase progresses to mononuclear cells and finally fibrosis with vessel wall destruction and microaneurysm formation.<br><br>Granulomatous inflammation (option A) characterises GPA, GCA, and Takayasu arteritis; IgA deposition in capillaries (option C) defines HSP; giant cells in the media (option D) feature in giant cell arteritis but not in PAN.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Ankylosing Spondylitis, syndesmophytes are:',o:['Fluid-filled sacs in the joints','Bony growths in the ear canal','Areas of bone erosion in the hip','Bony bridges between vertebrae due to ossification of ligaments'],a:3,e:`Syndesmophytes in ankylosing spondylitis are bony bridges between vertebrae from ossification of the annulus fibrosus and adjacent ligaments; they create the bamboo spine appearance.<br><br>Symmetric involvement of spine and sacroiliac joints leads to ankylosis (joint fusion). Bamboo spine reflects continuous fusion of vertebral bodies through marginal syndesmophytes. The disease is more common in males with HLA-B27.<br><br>Fluid-filled sacs (option A) describe ganglion cysts; bony growths in ear canal (option B) are exostoses unrelated to AS; bone erosion in the hip (option C) describes joint destruction not bridging bony growth.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Anaphylactoid purpura (HSP) is often preceded by:',o:['A heavy metal exposure','A fungal skin infection','An upper respiratory tract infection','A urinary tract infection'],a:2,e:`Anaphylactoid purpura (HSP) is often preceded by upper respiratory tract infection; viral or streptococcal pharyngitis triggers the IgA immune complex disease 1-2 weeks before purpura onset.<br><br>HSP is the most common childhood systemic vasculitis and often follows upper respiratory tract infection. Mesangial IgA deposits on renal biopsy mirror IgA nephropathy. Most cases are self-limiting.<br><br>Heavy metal exposure (option A) is not a recognised trigger; fungal skin infection (option B) does not precipitate IgA vasculitis; urinary tract infection (option D) is not a typical antecedent for HSP, which classically follows upper respiratory infection.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following lab findings is characteristic of Polyarteritis Nodosa?',o:['High levels of IgE','Positive p-ANCA (in a minority) but usually ANCA negative','Positive anti-dsDNA','Positive c-ANCA'],a:1,e:`Polyarteritis nodosa is usually ANCA negative, with positive p-ANCA only in a minority; this distinguishes PAN from ANCA-associated small-vessel vasculitides.<br><br>Hepatitis B seropositivity occurs in 30 percent of patients with PAN. Diagnosis relies on tissue biopsy showing transmural inflammation with fibrinoid necrosis or visceral angiography showing microaneurysms. ESR and CRP are typically elevated as non-specific markers.<br><br>High IgE (option A) is associated with Churg-Strauss eosinophilic granulomatosis; positive anti-dsDNA (option C) is specific for SLE; positive c-ANCA (option D) is associated with granulomatosis with polyangiitis (Wegener), not classical PAN.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 25-year-old patient with Ankylosing Spondylitis fails NSAID therapy. What is the next step in management?',o:['TNF-alpha inhibitors (e.g., Etanercept, Adalimumab)','High-dose oral Prednisone','Antibiotics','Total bed rest'],a:0,e:`TNF-alpha inhibitors (eg, etanercept, adalimumab) are next-line after NSAID failure in ankylosing spondylitis; biologic therapy reduces inflammation and may slow radiographic progression in axial disease.<br><br>Anti-TNF biologics show efficacy for axial and peripheral disease. IL-17 inhibitors (secukinumab, ixekizumab) are alternatives. Conventional DMARDs are ineffective for axial spondyloarthritis. Physiotherapy with daily exercise remains essential alongside pharmacological escalation.<br><br>High-dose oral prednisone (option B) has limited efficacy in axial disease; antibiotics (option C) treat infection not autoimmune spondylitis; total bed rest (option D) accelerates spinal stiffening and is contraindicated in inflammatory back pain.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Behcet\'s syndrome can involve the CNS, often presenting as:',o:['Peripheral neuropathy only','Meningoencephalitis or dural sinus thrombosis','Parkinsonism','Alzheimer\'s-like dementia'],a:1,e:`CNS Behcet syndrome often presents as meningoencephalitis or dural sinus thrombosis; parenchymal involvement targets brainstem and basal ganglia, while vascular involvement causes venous sinus thrombosis.<br><br>Neuro-Behcet carries significant morbidity and mortality. Parenchymal disease produces pyramidal signs, sphincter disturbance, and behavioural changes. MRI shows characteristic brainstem lesions. Treatment requires high-dose corticosteroids and immunosuppression with azathioprine or biologic agents long-term.<br><br>Peripheral neuropathy alone (option A) is uncommon in Behcet; parkinsonism (option C) is not a typical feature; Alzheimer-like dementia (option D) does not characterise Behcet CNS involvement, which has distinct meningoencephalitic and vascular patterns.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Small-vessel vasculitis is best exemplified by:',o:['Polyarteritis nodosa','Giant cell arteritis','Microscopic polyangiitis','Takayasu arteritis'],a:2,e:`Microscopic polyangiitis is a small-vessel vasculitis; necrotizing vasculitis commonly involves lung, kidneys, and skin with pauci-immune glomerulonephritis and palpable purpura without granulomas.<br><br>MPA shows MPO-ANCA/p-ANCA (anti-myeloperoxidase) positivity. Presentation is similar to granulomatosis with polyangiitis but without nasopharyngeal involvement. Treat with cyclophosphamide and corticosteroids; maintenance with rituximab or azathioprine after induction therapy.<br><br>Polyarteritis nodosa (option A) is a medium-vessel vasculitis; giant cell arteritis (option B) is a large-vessel vasculitis; Takayasu arteritis (option D) is also a large-vessel vasculitis affecting the aortic arch and great vessels.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In a child with Anaphylactoid purpura, what is the most important long-term follow-up requirement?',o:['Repeat joint X-rays','Serial echocardiograms','Monthly hearing tests','Blood pressure and urinalysis monitoring for renal involvement'],a:3,e:`Long-term follow-up of HSP requires blood pressure and urinalysis monitoring for renal involvement; nephritis can develop weeks to months after initial presentation, determining prognosis.<br><br>HSP nephritis ranges from mild haematuria to crescentic glomerulonephritis with progression to end-stage renal disease in a minority. Monitoring continues for at least six to twelve months. Persistent proteinuria warrants nephrology referral.<br><br>Repeat joint X-rays (option A) are unnecessary as arthritis is self-limiting; serial echocardiograms (option B) are not indicated; monthly hearing tests (option C) are irrelevant since HSP does not affect hearing or cochlear function.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Enthesitis in Ankylosing Spondylitis most commonly affects which site?',o:['Insertion of the Achilles tendon','Elbow','Finger joints','Wrist'],a:0,e:`Enthesitis in ankylosing spondylitis most commonly affects the insertion of the Achilles tendon; inflammation at the bone-tendon junction is a hallmark of seronegative spondyloarthritis.<br><br>Subtypes share variable inflammatory back pain, peripheral arthritis, enthesitis (inflamed insertion sites of tendons, eg, Achilles), dactylitis, and uveitis. Plantar fasciitis is another common enthesitis site. MRI detects active enthesitis early.<br><br>Elbow (option B) lateral epicondylitis is a non-spondyloarthritic enthesopathy; finger joints (option C) are sites of arthritis rather than enthesitis primarily; wrist (option D) is not a typical AS enthesitis location.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a cutaneous manifestation of Behcet’s syndrome?',o:['Malar rash','Heliotrope rash','Erythema nodosum','Livedo reticularis'],a:2,e:`Erythema nodosum is a cutaneous manifestation of Behcet syndrome; tender red nodules typically appear on the shins, reflecting septal panniculitis without vasculitis on biopsy.<br><br>Other Behcet skin lesions include papulopustular eruptions and pseudofolliculitis. Pathergy test (sterile pustule after needle prick) is included in diagnostic criteria. Skin lesions are part of clinical criteria for Behcet.<br><br>Malar rash (option A) is the butterfly rash of SLE; heliotrope rash (option B) is the periorbital violaceous discolouration of dermatomyositis; livedo reticularis (option D) is associated with antiphospholipid syndrome and polyarteritis nodosa.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Treatment of choice for Polyarteritis Nodosa (PAN) without Hepatitis B involvement is:',o:['Observation only','Aspirin only','Plasmapheresis only','Corticosteroids and Cyclophosphamide'],a:3,e:`Corticosteroids and cyclophosphamide are the treatment of choice for polyarteritis nodosa without hepatitis B involvement; combination immunosuppression induces remission in severe systemic disease.<br><br>Hepatitis B-associated PAN requires antiviral therapy and plasmapheresis with shorter immunosuppression. Five-factor score guides treatment intensity. Maintenance therapy with azathioprine follows induction. Treat with corticosteroids, cyclophosphamide as standard for non-viral PAN cases.<br><br>Observation only (option A) leads to high mortality in untreated PAN; aspirin only (option B) is inadequate for systemic vasculitis; plasmapheresis only (option C) is reserved for hepatitis B-associated cases as adjunctive therapy alongside antivirals.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with Ankylosing Spondylitis develops a restrictive lung pattern. This is primarily due to:',o:['Fusion of the costovertebral joints and chest wall rigidity','Asthma','Pulmonary fibrosis','Pleural effusion'],a:0,e:`Restrictive lung pattern in ankylosing spondylitis is primarily due to fusion of costovertebral joints and chest wall rigidity; fixed thoracic cage limits inspiratory expansion mechanically.<br><br>Pulmonary function tests show reduced vital capacity and total lung capacity. Apical fibrobullous disease may also occur but is less common than the chest wall restrictive component. Diaphragmatic compensation maintains adequate ventilation.<br><br>Asthma (option B) shows obstructive pattern with bronchodilator response; pulmonary fibrosis (option C) is uncommon in AS and would require parenchymal disease; pleural effusion (option D) does not typically complicate ankylosing spondylitis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Anaphylactoid purpura (HSP) is generally:',o:['A precursor to leukemia','A self-limiting condition with good prognosis in children','Highly contagious','A chronic, lifelong disease'],a:1,e:`Anaphylactoid purpura is generally a self-limiting condition with good prognosis in children; most cases resolve within four to six weeks without specific treatment.<br><br>HSP is the most common childhood systemic vasculitis. Renal involvement determines long-term prognosis with rare progression to end-stage renal disease. Recurrences occur in around one-third of patients but rarely require chronic immunosuppression.<br><br>Precursor to leukaemia (option A) is incorrect since HSP is not premalignant; highly contagious (option C) is wrong as HSP is autoimmune not infectious; chronic lifelong disease (option D) misrepresents the typically self-limiting paediatric course.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Polyarteritis nodosa is frequently associated with which viral infection?',o:['Influenza','HIV','Epstein-Barr Virus','Hepatitis B'],a:3,e:`Polyarteritis nodosa is frequently associated with hepatitis B; viral antigen-antibody immune complexes deposit in vessel walls of medium-sized arteries, driving the necrotising vasculitis.<br><br>Hepatitis B seropositivity occurs in 30 percent of PAN patients. Treatment differs from non-viral PAN, requiring antiviral therapy and plasmapheresis with limited immunosuppression. The association has decreased with widespread vaccination programmes.<br><br>Influenza (option A) is not a PAN trigger; HIV (option B) is not classically associated though may rarely produce similar vasculopathy; Epstein-Barr virus (option C) has no established association with classical polyarteritis nodosa.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a classic symptom of Ankylosing Spondylitis?',o:['Blurred vision that improves with light','Diarrhea','Buttock pain that alternates from side to side','Weight gain'],a:2,e:`Buttock pain alternating from side to side is a classic symptom of ankylosing spondylitis; alternating sacroiliac inflammation produces the characteristic shifting buttock discomfort.<br><br>Inflammatory back pain features include morning stiffness over 30 minutes, improvement with exercise, worsening with rest, and onset before age 45. Pain may radiate to posterior thighs but rarely below the knees.<br><br>Blurred vision improving with light (option A) is not characteristic; diarrhoea (option B) is not a typical symptom though IBD-associated AS exists; weight gain (option D) is not associated, with weight loss possible in active disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Behcet’s syndrome gastrointestinal involvement most commonly causes:',o:['Esophageal webs','Ileocecal ulcerations','Pancreatitis','Gastric polyps'],a:1,e:`Behcet syndrome gastrointestinal involvement most commonly causes ileocecal ulcerations; deep, punched-out ulcers in the terminal ileum and caecum mimic Crohn disease on endoscopy.<br><br>Histological distinction from Crohn requires absence of granulomas and presence of vasculitis. Complications include perforation, bleeding, and stricture formation. Management includes mesalamine, corticosteroids, immunosuppression, and surgery for perforation or refractory bleeding from ulcerative lesions.<br><br>Esophageal webs (option A) characterise Plummer-Vinson syndrome; pancreatitis (option C) is not a common Behcet feature; gastric polyps (option D) are not associated with Behcet syndrome and reflect entirely separate pathologic processes in the stomach.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The term "vasculitis" refers to:',o:['Inflammation of the blood vessel walls','Inflammation of the skin only','Inflammation of the joints','Inflammation of the nerves'],a:0,e:`Vasculitis refers to inflammation of the blood vessel walls; clinical manifestations depend on vessel size and organ distribution, ranging from skin purpura to aortic aneurysm.<br><br>Vasculitides are classified by vessel size: large (giant cell, Takayasu), medium (PAN, Kawasaki, Buerger), and small (granulomatosis with polyangiitis, microscopic polyangiitis, Churg-Strauss, HSP, hypersensitivity vasculitis). Pathogenesis involves immune complexes or ANCA.<br><br>Inflammation of skin only (option B) is dermatitis or panniculitis; inflammation of joints (option C) is arthritis; inflammation of nerves (option D) is neuritis, all distinct entities though some may complicate vasculitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is NOT part of the Modified New York Criteria for Ankylosing Spondylitis?',o:['Low back pain for >3 months improved by exercise','Positive rheumatoid factor','Limitation of lumbar spine motion','Radiographic evidence of sacroiliitis'],a:1,e:`Positive rheumatoid factor is NOT part of the Modified New York Criteria for ankylosing spondylitis; AS is by definition seronegative spondyloarthritis without rheumatoid factor positivity.<br><br>Modified New York Criteria require radiographic sacroiliitis plus at least one clinical criterion: low back pain over three months improved by exercise, limitation of lumbar spine motion, or limitation of chest expansion.<br><br>Low back pain improved by exercise (option A) is part of criteria; limitation of lumbar spine motion (option C) is included; radiographic sacroiliitis (option D) is mandatory; only RF positivity (option B) is incorrectly listed.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 10-year-old girl has purpura on her legs. Which finding would most likely rule OUT Anaphylactoid purpura?',o:['Normal platelet count','Normal coagulation studies','Low platelet count (thrombocytopenia)','Presence of joint pain'],a:2,e:`Low platelet count (thrombocytopenia) would rule out anaphylactoid purpura; HSP is associated with normal platelet counts despite the appearance of palpable purpura.<br><br>Coagulation studies are also normal in HSP. Thrombocytopenic purpura such as ITP, TTP, or DIC presents with low platelet counts and warrants different investigation. Distinguishing palpable from non-palpable purpura is key.<br><br>Normal platelet count (option A) is consistent with HSP; normal coagulation studies (option B) also fit; presence of joint pain (option D) is part of the classic HSP triad and would support rather than rule out the diagnosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Testicular pain or tenderness is a classic clinical clue for:',o:['Osteopetrosis','Ankylosing spondylitis','Sjogren’s syndrome','Polyarteritis nodosa'],a:3,e:`Testicular pain or tenderness is a classic clinical clue for polyarteritis nodosa; vasculitic involvement of testicular arteries produces orchialgia, sometimes mimicking torsion or epididymitis.<br><br>Other PAN features include fever, weight loss, malaise, abdominal pain, melena, hypertension, livedo reticularis, mononeuritis multiplex, and renal damage with microaneurysms. Testicular biopsy occasionally provides diagnostic histology when other accessible tissue is uninvolved.<br><br>Osteopetrosis (option A) is a metabolic bone disorder; ankylosing spondylitis (option B) does not affect testes; Sjogren syndrome (option C) targets exocrine glands without testicular involvement, distinguishing all three from polyarteritis nodosa clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'"Dagger sign" on a spinal X-ray refers to:',o:['Ossification of the supraspinous and interspinous ligaments','A herniated disc','Scoliosis','A fracture of the dens'],a:0,e:`Dagger sign on spinal X-ray refers to ossification of the supraspinous and interspinous ligaments; the central radiopaque line in the lumbar spine resembles a dagger blade.<br><br>The dagger sign accompanies bamboo spine in advanced ankylosing spondylitis. Interspinous ligament ossification produces the central density, while bilateral facet joint and sacroiliac fusion complete the radiographic picture.<br><br>Herniated disc (option B) is a focal soft tissue lesion not visible on plain X-ray; scoliosis (option C) is lateral spinal curvature; fracture of the dens (option D) is C2 odontoid injury, anatomically and pathologically unrelated to AS.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the characteristic distribution of Behcet’s oral ulcers?',o:['They are painless','They never recur','They are usually the first symptom and occur in crops','They are always found on the tongue only'],a:2,e:`Behcet oral ulcers are usually the first symptom and occur in crops; recurrent painful aphthous ulcers in buccal mucosa, tongue, and lips appear at least three times per year.<br><br>Oral ulcers precede other manifestations by years in many patients. Diagnostic criteria require recurrent oral ulceration plus two of: genital ulcers, eye lesions, skin lesions, or positive pathergy test.<br><br>Painless ulcers (option A) suggest syphilis or oral cancer; never-recurring ulcers (option B) would not meet criteria requiring recurrence; tongue-only distribution (option D) is not characteristic, since Behcet ulcers occur throughout oral mucosa.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In systemic vasculitis, a "palpable purpura" is a clinical hallmark of:',o:['Small vessel vasculitis','Nerve ischemia','Large vessel involvement','Bone marrow failure'],a:0,e:`Palpable purpura is a clinical hallmark of small vessel vasculitis; immune complex or ANCA-mediated injury to capillaries and post-capillary venules produces the raised purpuric lesions.<br><br>Small-vessel vasculitis includes granulomatosis with polyangiitis, microscopic polyangiitis, eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis, HSP, and hypersensitivity vasculitis. Skin biopsy shows leukocytoclastic vasculitis with neutrophil fragmentation around vessel walls confirming the histological diagnosis pathologically.<br><br>Nerve ischaemia (option B) produces mononeuritis multiplex from medium-vessel vasculitis; large vessel involvement (option C) causes pulse deficits and bruits not purpura; bone marrow failure (option D) produces non-palpable petechiae from thrombocytopenia.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 72-year-old woman presents with a new, throbbing headache and pain in her jaw when chewing. Her ESR is 95 mm/hr. What is the most important immediate step to prevent permanent complications?',o:['Prescribe low-dose Aspirin only','Wait for temporal artery biopsy results','Order an urgent CT of the head','Start high-dose intravenous or oral corticosteroids'],a:3,e:`Start high-dose corticosteroids immediately; suspected giant cell arteritis with headache, jaw claudication, and ESR 95 must receive prompt steroids before biopsy to prevent blindness.<br><br>Treat with high-dose corticosteroids prior to temporal artery biopsy to prevent blindness. Biopsy remains positive for several days after steroid initiation, so empirical treatment does not preclude diagnosis.<br><br>Low-dose aspirin only (option A) is inadequate for active vasculitis; waiting for biopsy results (option B) risks irreversible vision loss; CT head (option C) is not diagnostic for GCA and delays definitive vision-saving steroid therapy.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (formerly Wegener’s) is most strongly associated with which of the following laboratory markers?',o:['p-ANCA (anti-MPO)','c-ANCA (anti-PR3)','Anti-dsDNA','Anti-centromere'],a:1,e:`Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (Wegener) is associated with c-ANCA (anti-PR3); the antibody targets proteinase 3 in neutrophil cytoplasmic granules, producing the cytoplasmic immunofluorescence pattern.<br><br>Triad of focal necrotising vasculitis, necrotising granulomas in lung and upper airway, and necrotising glomerulonephritis. Treat with cyclophosphamide and corticosteroids. Rituximab is an alternative induction agent. Maintenance therapy continues for at least one to two years.<br><br>p-ANCA (anti-MPO) (option A) is associated with microscopic polyangiitis and Churg-Strauss; anti-dsDNA (option C) is specific for SLE; anti-centromere (option D) is associated with limited cutaneous systemic sclerosis (CREST syndrome).<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 28-year-old Asian female presents with fatigue and a significant blood pressure discrepancy between her right and left arms. She has an audible bruit over the carotid artery. What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Temporal arteritis','Polyarteritis nodosa','Takayasu’s arteritis','Thromboangiitis obliterans'],a:2,e:`Takayasu arteritis is the diagnosis; young Asian female with blood pressure discrepancy between arms reflects pulseless disease from aortic arch and great vessel narrowing.<br><br>Takayasu is usually Asian females under 40 with weak upper extremity pulses, fever, night sweats, arthritis, myalgias, skin nodules, and ocular disturbances. Granulomatous thickening and narrowing of aortic arch and proximal great vessels causes the clinical features.<br><br>Temporal arteritis (option A) affects elderly with headache and jaw claudication; polyarteritis nodosa (option B) is medium-vessel without large-vessel narrowing; thromboangiitis obliterans (option D) affects distal extremity vessels in heavy smokers.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Thromboangiitis obliterans (Buerger’s disease) is most strongly linked to which of the following?',o:['Intravenous drug use','High cholesterol','Chronic alcohol use','Heavy cigarette smoking'],a:3,e:`Buerger disease (thromboangiitis obliterans) is most strongly linked to heavy cigarette smoking; tobacco exposure is essentially mandatory for disease development and maintenance.<br><br>Heavy smokers, males under 40 are typical patients. Intermittent claudication may lead to gangrene, autoamputation of digits, and superficial nodular phlebitis. Raynaud phenomenon is often present. Treatment is complete smoking cessation.<br><br>Intravenous drug use (option A) causes other vascular complications; high cholesterol (option B) is the atherosclerosis substrate, distinct from Buerger; chronic alcohol use (option C) causes liver and pancreatic disease, not the segmental thrombosing vasculitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 35-year-old African American female presents with a dry cough, shortness of breath, and painful red bumps on her shins (erythema nodosum). Chest X-ray shows bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy. What is the likely diagnosis?',o:['Sarcoidosis','Hypersensitivity vasculitis','Wegener’s granulomatosis','Tuberculosis'],a:0,e:`Sarcoidosis is the most likely diagnosis; African American female with cough, dyspnoea, and erythema nodosum on shins fits classic Lofgren syndrome presentation of acute sarcoid.<br><br>Sarcoidosis is characterised by immune-mediated, widespread non-caseating granulomas, elevated serum ACE levels, and elevated CD4/CD8 ratio in bronchoalveolar lavage. More common in African American females. CXR shows bilateral hilar adenopathy and reticular opacities.<br><br>Hypersensitivity vasculitis (option B) presents with palpable purpura on lower extremities; Wegener granulomatosis (option C) shows upper airway and renal disease with c-ANCA; tuberculosis (option D) shows caseating granulomas with positive AFB stains.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Wegener’s granulomatosis, the classic clinical triad involves the upper respiratory tract, the lungs, and the:',o:['Liver','Kidneys (Glomerulonephritis)','Brain','Heart'],a:1,e:`Wegener granulomatosis classic clinical triad involves the upper respiratory tract, lungs, and kidneys (glomerulonephritis); ELK mnemonic captures the three major organ systems involved.<br><br>Triad: focal necrotising vasculitis, necrotising granulomas in lung and upper airway, necrotising glomerulonephritis. Upper respiratory: nasal septum perforation, chronic sinusitis, otitis media. Lower respiratory: haemoptysis, cough, dyspnoea. Renal: haematuria, red cell casts.<br><br>Liver (option A) is not a classical Wegener target; brain (option C) is uncommonly involved despite occasional CNS vasculitis; heart (option D) involvement is rare in Wegener compared to the dominant upper airway, pulmonary, and renal triad.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the "gold standard" for the diagnosis of Temporal Arteritis?',o:['Temporal artery biopsy','MRI of the brain','Angiography of the aortic arch','Serum ACE levels'],a:0,e:`Temporal artery biopsy is the gold standard for temporal arteritis diagnosis; histology shows focal granulomatous inflammation with multinucleated giant cells in the arterial media.<br><br>Treat with high-dose corticosteroids prior to biopsy to prevent blindness. Biopsy remains positive for days after steroid initiation. Skip lesions may produce false negatives, so a 2-3 cm specimen and serial sectioning improve yield.<br><br>MRI brain (option B) is not diagnostic; angiography of aortic arch (option C) is used in Takayasu arteritis; serum ACE levels (option D) are elevated in sarcoidosis, all differing from the histological gold standard.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient presents with "palpable purpura" limited to the skin after starting a new sulfonamide antibiotic. Labs show no internal organ involvement. This is characteristic of:',o:['Takayasu’s arteritis','Buerger’s disease','Hypersensitivity vasculitis (Leukocytoclastic vasculitis)','Sarcoidosis'],a:2,e:`Hypersensitivity vasculitis (leukocytoclastic vasculitis) is the diagnosis; palpable purpura limited to skin after starting a sulfonamide antibiotic without internal organ involvement is classic.<br><br>Drugs (NSAIDs, antibiotics including sulfonamides and penicillins) and infections are the most common triggers. Skin biopsy shows leukocytoclastic vasculitis. Withdrawal of the offending drug typically produces resolution within days to weeks without specific immunosuppressive therapy required.<br><br>Takayasu arteritis (option A) affects large vessels with pulseless disease; Buerger disease (option B) affects distal extremity vessels in smokers; sarcoidosis (option D) features non-caseating granulomas and bilateral hilar adenopathy without drug-triggered purpura.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a common radiographic finding in a patient with Sarcoidosis?',o:['"Bamboo spine"','Bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy','"String of beads" appearance','"Punched-out" lytic lesions'],a:1,e:`Bilateral hilar lymphadenopathy is a common radiographic finding in sarcoidosis; CXR shows bilateral hilar adenopathy and coarse reticular opacities, with CT chest demonstrating extensive hilar and mediastinal adenopathy.<br><br>Sarcoidosis is characterised by immune-mediated, widespread non-caseating granulomas, elevated serum ACE levels, and elevated CD4/CD8 ratio in bronchoalveolar lavage. Most common in African American females.<br><br>Bamboo spine (option A) is the radiographic hallmark of advanced ankylosing spondylitis; string of beads (option C) characterises polyarteritis nodosa on angiography; punched-out lytic lesions (option D) are seen in multiple myeloma not sarcoidosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Buerger’s disease (Thromboangiitis obliterans) primarily affects which vessels?',o:['Aorta and its major branches','Capillaries of the lungs','Large veins of the pelvis','Small and medium-sized arteries and veins of the extremities'],a:3,e:`Buerger disease primarily affects small and medium-sized arteries and veins of the extremities; segmental thrombosing vasculitis involves distal vessels causing ischaemia and gangrene of digits.<br><br>Heavy smokers, males under 40 are typical patients. Intermittent claudication may lead to gangrene, autoamputation of digits, and superficial nodular phlebitis. Raynaud phenomenon is often present. Treatment is complete smoking cessation.<br><br>Aorta and major branches (option A) are affected in Takayasu arteritis; pulmonary capillaries (option B) are not Buerger targets; large pelvic veins (option C) are not affected by Buerger, which preferentially involves distal extremity vessels.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Sarcoidosis, the pathological hallmark is the presence of:',o:['Fibrinoid necrosis','Caseating granulomas','Non-caseating granulomas','Aschoff bodies'],a:2,e:`Non-caseating granulomas are the pathological hallmark of sarcoidosis; granulomas lack central necrosis, distinguishing them from caseating granulomas of tuberculosis and other infections.<br><br>Sarcoidosis features immune-mediated, widespread non-caseating granulomas with epithelioid macrophages, multinucleated giant cells, and surrounding lymphocytes. Schaumann and asteroid bodies appear within giant cells. Elevated serum ACE and elevated CD4/CD8 ratio in bronchoalveolar lavage support diagnosis.<br><br>Fibrinoid necrosis (option A) characterises polyarteritis nodosa and other vasculitides; caseating granulomas (option B) define tuberculosis; Aschoff bodies (option D) are seen in acute rheumatic fever as pathognomonic granulomatous myocardial lesions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 55-year-old male presents with chronic sinusitis, bloody nasal discharge, and a "saddle-nose" deformity. Which condition should be suspected?',o:['Wegener’s granulomatosis','Sarcoidosis','Buerger’s disease','Takayasu’s arteritis'],a:0,e:`Wegener granulomatosis is the suspected diagnosis; chronic sinusitis, bloody nasal discharge, and saddle-nose deformity reflect upper respiratory tract granulomatous destruction characteristic of granulomatosis with polyangiitis.<br><br>Upper respiratory tract: perforation of nasal septum, chronic sinusitis, otitis media, mastoiditis. Lower respiratory tract: haemoptysis, cough, dyspnoea. Renal: haematuria, red cell casts. PR3-ANCA/c-ANCA positivity supports diagnosis. Treat with cyclophosphamide and corticosteroids.<br><br>Sarcoidosis (option B) does not produce nasal septal perforation typically; Buerger disease (option C) affects distal extremity vessels; Takayasu arteritis (option D) affects the aortic arch and produces pulseless disease without upper airway destruction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Polymyalgia rheumatica (PMR), characterized by aching and stiffness in the shoulders and hips, is closely associated with which vasculitis?',o:['Takayasu’s arteritis','Temporal (Giant Cell) arteritis','Wegener’s granulomatosis','Polyarteritis nodosa'],a:1,e:`Polymyalgia rheumatica is closely associated with temporal (giant cell) arteritis; up to 50 percent of GCA patients have PMR features, and around 15 percent of PMR patients develop GCA.<br><br>PMR features pain and stiffness in shoulders and hips, often with fever, malaise, weight loss, in women over 50. Elevated ESR and CRP with normal CK. Rapid response to low-dose corticosteroids.<br><br>Takayasu arteritis (option A) affects younger patients; Wegener granulomatosis (option C) is small-vessel disease with c-ANCA; polyarteritis nodosa (option D) is medium-vessel without the polymyalgia rheumatica association characteristic of giant cell arteritis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which enzyme is frequently elevated in the serum of patients with active Sarcoidosis?',o:['Amylase','Creatine kinase','Alkaline phosphatase','Angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE)'],a:3,e:`Angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) is frequently elevated in active sarcoidosis; macrophages within granulomas secrete the enzyme, raising serum levels in 60 percent of active cases.<br><br>Elevated serum ACE supports the diagnosis but is not specific. Elevated CD4/CD8 ratio in bronchoalveolar lavage and non-caseating granulomas on biopsy provide more definitive evidence. ACE may follow disease activity during monitoring.<br><br>Amylase (option A) is elevated in pancreatitis; creatine kinase (option B) is elevated in muscle disease and myocardial infarction; alkaline phosphatase (option C) is elevated in liver and bone disease, none specific to sarcoidosis activity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the definitive treatment for Buerger’s disease?',o:['High-dose Prednisone','Complete smoking cessation','Methotrexate','Warfarin therapy'],a:1,e:`Complete smoking cessation is the definitive treatment for Buerger disease; tobacco exposure drives disease and continued use leads to inevitable progression with gangrene and amputation.<br><br>No pharmacological therapy halts disease progression in continuing smokers. Even occasional exposure may trigger relapse. Sympathectomy and bypass surgery offer limited benefit since distal vessels are typically too small for revascularisation.<br><br>High-dose prednisone (option A) does not halt smoking-driven disease; methotrexate (option C) has no proven role; warfarin therapy (option D) does not address the underlying inflammatory and thrombotic process specific to ongoing tobacco exposure.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Takayasu’s arteritis is often referred to as:',o:['"Stiff person syndrome"','"Cotton wool disease"','"Strawberry tongue disease"','"Pulseless disease"'],a:3,e:`Takayasu arteritis is often referred to as pulseless disease; granulomatous narrowing of aortic arch and proximal great vessels reduces upper extremity pulses, producing the eponymous hallmark.<br><br>Usually Asian females under 40 with weak upper extremity pulses, fever, night sweats, arthritis, myalgias, skin nodules, and ocular disturbances. ESR is elevated. Treat with corticosteroids.<br><br>Stiff person syndrome (option A) is a neurological autoimmune disorder; cotton wool disease (option B) is not standard nomenclature; strawberry tongue (option C) is a feature of Kawasaki disease and scarlet fever, unrelated to Takayasu.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 40-year-old man presents with cough and hemoptysis. Chest CT shows cavitary nodules. Biopsy of a nodule shows necrotizing granulomatous inflammation. This is consistent with:',o:['Wegener’s granulomatosis','Hypersensitivity vasculitis','Sarcoidosis','Temporal arteritis'],a:0,e:`Wegener granulomatosis is the diagnosis; cough, haemoptysis, cavitary lung nodules, and biopsy showing necrotising granulomatous inflammation define granulomatosis with polyangiitis pulmonary involvement.<br><br>CXR: large nodular densities. Cavitation occurs in many lesions. The triad of focal necrotising vasculitis, necrotising granulomas in lung and upper airway, and necrotising glomerulonephritis defines Wegener. PR3-ANCA/c-ANCA positivity supports the diagnosis.<br><br>Hypersensitivity vasculitis (option B) is skin-limited without lung cavitation; sarcoidosis (option C) produces hilar adenopathy with non-caseating granulomas without cavitation; temporal arteritis (option D) affects the temporal artery without pulmonary involvement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hypersensitivity vasculitis is most commonly triggered by:',o:['Genetic mutations in collagen','Excessive vitamin D','Drugs (e.g., NSAIDs, Antibiotics) or infections','Chronic hypertension'],a:2,e:`Hypersensitivity vasculitis is most commonly triggered by drugs (NSAIDs, antibiotics) or infections; type III immune complex deposition in post-capillary venules produces the leukocytoclastic vasculitis pattern.<br><br>Skin biopsy shows leukocytoclastic vasculitis confirming diagnosis. Withdrawal of the offending drug typically produces resolution within days to weeks. Severe cases may require short courses of corticosteroids. Internal organ involvement is uncommon.<br><br>Genetic mutations in collagen (option A) cause connective tissue disorders not vasculitis; excessive vitamin D (option B) causes hypercalcaemia not vasculitis; chronic hypertension (option D) damages vessels through mechanical stress, not the immune-complex hypersensitivity mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Sarcoidosis, hypercalcemia occurs due to:',o:['Increased 1-alpha-hydroxylase activity in macrophages within granulomas','Parathyroid gland adenoma','Excessive intake of milk','Bone destruction by tumors'],a:0,e:`Hypercalcaemia in sarcoidosis occurs due to increased 1-alpha-hydroxylase activity in macrophages within granulomas; ectopic vitamin D activation increases intestinal calcium absorption, producing hypercalcaemia.<br><br>PTH is suppressed appropriately. Sun exposure may aggravate hypercalcaemia by increasing substrate availability. Treatment includes hydration, corticosteroids (which suppress macrophage 1-alpha-hydroxylase), and avoidance of vitamin D supplementation. Hypercalciuria with nephrolithiasis is a related complication.<br><br>Parathyroid adenoma (option B) causes primary hyperparathyroidism with elevated PTH; excessive milk intake (option C) is the milk-alkali syndrome; bone destruction by tumour (option D) reflects metastatic or myeloma bone disease, not the granulomatous mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which ophthalmologic finding is common in Sarcoidosis?',o:['Cataracts only','Anterior uveitis','Retinal detachment','Glaucoma only'],a:1,e:`Anterior uveitis is a common ophthalmologic finding in sarcoidosis; granulomatous inflammation of the iris and ciliary body produces painful red eye with photophobia.<br><br>Sarcoidosis is associated with restrictive lung disease (interstitial fibrosis), erythema nodosum, lupus pernio, Bell palsy, epithelioid granulomas containing Schaumann and asteroid bodies, uveitis, and hypercalcaemia. Treatment includes topical and systemic corticosteroids.<br><br>Cataracts only (option A) is non-specific; retinal detachment (option C) is not a typical sarcoidosis complication; glaucoma only (option D) is incomplete since sarcoid eye disease is dominated by granulomatous uveitis rather than isolated intraocular pressure elevation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 75-year-old man has a biopsy of his temporal artery. The pathology report mentions "fragmentation of the internal elastic lamina" and "giant cells." This confirms:',o:['Takayasu’s arteritis','Wegener’s granulomatosis','Polyarteritis nodosa','Giant Cell (Temporal) arteritis'],a:3,e:`Giant cell (temporal) arteritis is the diagnosis; fragmentation of the internal elastic lamina with multinucleated giant cells in the arterial media is the histological hallmark of GCA.<br><br>Most commonly affects branches of carotid artery. Focal granulomatous inflammation. ESR is markedly elevated. Treat with high-dose corticosteroids prior to temporal artery biopsy to prevent blindness from ophthalmic artery occlusion.<br><br>Takayasu arteritis (option A) shares granulomatous histology but affects aortic arch in young Asian females; Wegener granulomatosis (option B) shows necrotising granulomas; polyarteritis nodosa (option C) shows transmural inflammation with fibrinoid necrosis without giant cells.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Takayasu’s arteritis primarily affects:',o:['The small vessels of the feet','The coronary arteries only','The aorta and its primary branches','The veins of the lower legs'],a:2,e:`Takayasu arteritis primarily affects the aorta and its primary branches; granulomatous thickening and narrowing of the aortic arch and proximal great vessels produce pulseless disease.<br><br>Usually Asian females under 40. Pulseless disease (weak upper extremity pulses), fever, night sweats, arthritis, myalgias, skin nodules. Treat with corticosteroids; biologics added in refractory disease.<br><br>Small vessels of the feet (option A) are affected in Buerger disease; coronary arteries only (option B) is not the Takayasu pattern though aortic arch involvement may extend; veins of lower legs (option D) are not Takayasu targets.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the most common symptom of Buerger’s disease?',o:['Hemoptysis','Malar rash','Facial swelling','Distal extremity ischemia (claudication, ulcers, or gangrene)'],a:3,e:`Distal extremity ischaemia (claudication, ulcers, or gangrene) is the most common Buerger disease symptom; segmental thrombosing vasculitis of small and medium distal vessels produces ischaemic complications.<br><br>Heavy smokers, males under 40 are typical patients. Intermittent claudication may lead to gangrene, autoamputation of digits, and superficial nodular phlebitis. Raynaud phenomenon is often present. Treatment is smoking cessation.<br><br>Haemoptysis (option A) is not a Buerger symptom; malar rash (option B) is an SLE feature; facial swelling (option C) is not associated with Buerger disease, which characteristically affects distal extremities rather than craniofacial structures.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with Wegener’s granulomatosis develops hematuria and RBC casts. The most likely finding on renal biopsy is:',o:['Pauci-immune necrotizing crescentic glomerulonephritis','IgA nephropathy','Minimal change disease','Membranous nephropathy'],a:0,e:`Pauci-immune necrotising crescentic glomerulonephritis is the renal biopsy finding in Wegener granulomatosis; minimal immune deposits with focal segmental crescentic injury reflects ANCA-driven pathogenesis.<br><br>Renal: haematuria, red cell casts. Triad of focal necrotising vasculitis, necrotising granulomas in lung and upper airway, and necrotising glomerulonephritis. PR3-ANCA/c-ANCA positivity supports diagnosis. Treat with cyclophosphamide and corticosteroids.<br><br>IgA nephropathy (option B) shows mesangial IgA deposits seen in HSP and Berger disease; minimal change disease (option C) shows normal light microscopy with effaced foot processes; membranous nephropathy (option D) shows subepithelial deposits.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Löfgren’s syndrome is a specific acute presentation of Sarcoidosis characterized by:',o:['Blindness, headache, and jaw pain','Hematuria, sinusitis, and weight loss','Hilar lymphadenopathy, erythema nodosum, and polyarthritis','Fever, splenomegaly, and anemia'],a:2,e:`Lofgren syndrome features hilar lymphadenopathy, erythema nodosum, and polyarthritis; this acute presentation of sarcoidosis carries an excellent prognosis with high rates of spontaneous remission.<br><br>Lofgren syndrome typically presents in young women. Fever and ankle periarthritis often accompany the triad. NSAIDs and short courses of corticosteroids manage symptoms. Spontaneous resolution occurs in over 80 percent within 1-2 years without long-term sequelae.<br><br>Blindness, headache, jaw pain (option A) describes giant cell arteritis; haematuria, sinusitis, weight loss (option B) describes Wegener granulomatosis; fever, splenomegaly, anaemia (option D) is non-specific without sarcoid features specifically present here.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is a potential dermatological manifestation of Sarcoidosis?',o:['Target lesions','Lupus pernio (violaceous skin lesions on the nose/cheeks)','Honey-crusted crusts','Palpable purpura'],a:1,e:`Lupus pernio (violaceous skin lesions on the nose and cheeks) is a dermatological manifestation of sarcoidosis; chronic indurated plaques resemble systemic lupus erythematosus, hence the name.<br><br>Sarcoidosis is associated with restrictive lung disease (interstitial fibrosis), erythema nodosum, lupus pernio, Bell palsy, epithelioid granulomas containing Schaumann and asteroid bodies, uveitis, and hypercalcaemia. Skin biopsy reveals non-caseating granulomas.<br><br>Target lesions (option A) characterise erythema multiforme; honey-crusted lesions (option C) are typical of impetigo; palpable purpura (option D) is the cutaneous hallmark of small-vessel vasculitis, distinct from the indurated plaques of lupus pernio.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Hypersensitivity Vasculitis, the lesions are typically:',o:['Migratory','Occurring only on the scalp','Found only in the mouth','All at the same stage of development'],a:3,e:`Lesions in hypersensitivity vasculitis are typically all at the same stage of development; simultaneous appearance of palpable purpura on dependent areas reflects single-event immune complex deposition.<br><br>Skin biopsy shows leukocytoclastic vasculitis. The synchronous lesion pattern distinguishes it from chronic active vasculitides where lesions appear at varied stages. Withdrawal of the offending drug typically produces resolution within days to weeks.<br><br>Migratory lesions (option A) suggest erythema migrans or rheumatic fever; scalp-only distribution (option B) is unusual; oral cavity-only lesions (option C) suggest Behcet syndrome rather than the lower-extremity skin distribution of hypersensitivity vasculitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Temporal arteritis is a medical emergency because it can lead to:',o:['Permanent ischemic optic neuropathy (blindness)','Liver cirrhosis','Skin cancer','Renal failure'],a:0,e:`Permanent ischaemic optic neuropathy (blindness) makes temporal arteritis a medical emergency; ophthalmic artery occlusion produces irreversible vision loss without prompt corticosteroid intervention.<br><br>Treat with high-dose corticosteroids prior to temporal artery biopsy to prevent blindness. Bilateral involvement may follow within days if untreated. Tocilizumab is a steroid-sparing biologic for refractory or relapsing disease.<br><br>Liver cirrhosis (option B) is unrelated to GCA; skin cancer (option C) is not a complication; renal failure (option D) is not a typical GCA outcome, distinguishing it from systemic vasculitides like polyarteritis nodosa or Wegener.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Takayasu’s arteritis is most common in which demographic?',o:['Newborn infants','Children under 5','Young women of Asian descent','Elderly Caucasian males'],a:2,e:`Takayasu arteritis is most common in young women of Asian descent; the demographic distribution is sharply skewed toward East Asian females under 40 years of age.<br><br>Usually Asian females under 40 with pulseless disease (weak upper extremity pulses), fever, night sweats, arthritis, myalgias, skin nodules, and ocular disturbances. Granulomatous thickening and narrowing of aortic arch causes the features.<br><br>Newborn infants (option A) develop Kawasaki disease in early childhood; children under 5 (option B) have Kawasaki rather than Takayasu; elderly Caucasian males (option D) develop giant cell arteritis, contrasting demographically with Takayasu.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Wegener\'s granulomatosis, cyclophosphamide is often used in combination with:',o:['Insulin','Corticosteroids','Antihistamines','Antibiotics only'],a:1,e:`Cyclophosphamide is combined with corticosteroids in Wegener granulomatosis; this dual immunosuppressive induction reliably achieves remission in severe ANCA-associated vasculitis with renal involvement.<br><br>Rituximab is an alternative induction agent. Maintenance therapy with azathioprine, methotrexate, or rituximab continues for at least one to two years. Plasmapheresis is added for severe alveolar haemorrhage or rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis with dialysis-dependent renal failure.<br><br>Insulin (option A) treats diabetes; antihistamines (option C) treat allergic conditions; antibiotics only (option D) address infection but do not target the underlying autoimmune granulomatous inflammation requiring cytotoxic and immunosuppressive combination therapy.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Buerger’s disease can be distinguished from atherosclerosis by:',o:['The age of the patient (usually younger) and involvement of small distal vessels','The presence of high cholesterol','It cannot be distinguished','The presence of diabetes'],a:0,e:`Buerger disease is distinguished from atherosclerosis by patient age (usually younger) and involvement of small distal vessels; distal small-vessel pattern in heavy-smoking young males is characteristic.<br><br>Atherosclerosis affects older patients with classic risk factors and large/medium proximal vessels. Buerger affects males under 40 with heavy tobacco exposure and distal small vessels, producing distinctive corkscrew collaterals on angiography.<br><br>High cholesterol (option B) is the substrate of atherosclerosis, not Buerger; cannot be distinguished (option C) is wrong since clear clinical and angiographic features differ; diabetes (option D) is an atherosclerosis risk factor, not Buerger-defining.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 30-year-old male with Sarcoidosis presents with facial nerve palsy. This involvement of the nervous system is called:',o:['Multiple sclerosis','Neurosarcoidosis','Guillain-Barré syndrome','Mononeuritis multiplex'],a:1,e:`Neurosarcoidosis is the involvement of the nervous system by sarcoidosis; facial nerve palsy is the most common cranial neuropathy from granulomatous infiltration of meninges and cranial nerves.<br><br>Sarcoidosis affects cranial nerves (especially facial), hypothalamus, pituitary, meninges, and parenchyma. MRI may show enhancing leptomeningeal disease. CSF examination shows elevated protein and lymphocytic pleocytosis. Corticosteroids and steroid-sparing immunosuppressants are required.<br><br>Multiple sclerosis (option A) is a demyelinating disease; Guillain-Barre syndrome (option C) is acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy; mononeuritis multiplex (option D) reflects vasculitic neuropathy from PAN or Churg-Strauss, not granulomatous CNS disease.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The Kveim-Siltzbach skin test was historically used to diagnose:',o:['Buerger’s disease','Temporal arteritis','Wegener’s','Sarcoidosis'],a:3,e:`The Kveim-Siltzbach skin test was historically used to diagnose sarcoidosis; intradermal injection of sarcoid spleen extract produced a granulomatous reaction at 4-6 weeks in patients.<br><br>The test is no longer used due to lack of standardised antigen and risk of disease transmission. Modern diagnosis relies on tissue biopsy showing non-caseating granulomas, elevated serum ACE, elevated CD4/CD8 ratio in BAL.<br><br>Buerger disease (option A) is diagnosed clinically and angiographically; temporal arteritis (option B) requires biopsy; Wegener granulomatosis (option C) is diagnosed by ANCA serology and tissue biopsy, none using the Kveim-Siltzbach test.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Takayasu’s arteritis, the "late stage" is characterized by:',o:['Joint swelling','Acute skin rashes','Vascular stenosis and bruits','Fever and night sweats'],a:2,e:`Vascular stenosis and bruits characterise the late stage of Takayasu arteritis; chronic granulomatous inflammation produces fibrotic narrowing of the aorta and its branches with bruits.<br><br>Late-stage features include limb claudication, hypertension from renal artery stenosis, syncope, and stroke from vertebral or carotid disease. Imaging with MR or CT angiography demonstrates vessel wall thickening.<br><br>Joint swelling (option A) occurs early but is non-specific; acute skin rashes (option B) are not late features; fever and night sweats (option D) reflect the early prepulseless inflammatory phase rather than the late fibrotic stenotic stage.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following is true regarding Temporal Arteritis?',o:['It is caused by a virus','It is a systemic vasculitis that can involve the aorta','ESR is usually normal','It only affects the temporal artery'],a:1,e:`Temporal arteritis is a systemic vasculitis that can involve the aorta; aortic involvement may produce thoracic aortic aneurysm with risk of dissection on long-term follow-up.<br><br>Most commonly affects branches of carotid artery, but disease extends to involve the aorta and its primary branches in significant subset of patients. ESR is markedly elevated.<br><br>Caused by a virus (option A) is incorrect since GCA is autoimmune; ESR usually normal (option C) is wrong since ESR is markedly elevated; only affects temporal artery (option D) is wrong since GCA involves multiple branches.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The diagnosis of Hypersensitivity Vasculitis is confirmed by:',o:['MRI of the legs','Blood culture','Serum c-ANCA','Skin biopsy showing leukocytoclastic vasculitis'],a:3,e:`Skin biopsy showing leukocytoclastic vasculitis confirms hypersensitivity vasculitis; neutrophil fragmentation around small vessels with fibrinoid necrosis defines the histological pattern.<br><br>Drugs (NSAIDs, antibiotics) and infections are the most common triggers. Direct immunofluorescence may show immunoglobulin and complement deposits. Withdrawal of the offending drug typically produces resolution within days to weeks without specific systemic immunosuppression in most patients.<br><br>MRI of the legs (option A) is unhelpful for skin-limited vasculitis; blood culture (option B) excludes infection rather than confirming vasculitis; serum c-ANCA (option C) is associated with Wegener granulomatosis, not hypersensitivity vasculitis specifically diagnostically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A "corkscrew" appearance of collateral vessels on angiography is a classic sign of:',o:['Buerger’s disease','Takayasu’s arteritis','Temporal arteritis','Polyarteritis nodosa'],a:0,e:`Corkscrew appearance of collateral vessels on angiography is a classic Buerger disease sign; tortuous distal collaterals develop around segmental occlusions in extremity vessels.<br><br>Heavy smokers, males under 40 are typical patients. Segmental thrombosing vasculitis affects small and medium distal vessels. The corkscrew collaterals reflect the body's attempt to bypass occluded segments and are diagnostic on angiography.<br><br>Takayasu arteritis (option B) shows long-segment narrowing of aortic arch and great vessels; temporal arteritis (option C) does not produce corkscrew collaterals; polyarteritis nodosa (option D) shows microaneurysms and beading, not corkscrew patterns.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Wegener’s granulomatosis, "pauci-immune" refers to:',o:['Lack of white blood cells','Resistance to steroids','Minimal or absent immunoglobulin/complement deposition on staining','Total lack of immune system'],a:2,e:`Pauci-immune in Wegener granulomatosis refers to minimal or absent immunoglobulin or complement deposition on staining; the term contrasts with immune complex-mediated glomerulonephritis.<br><br>ANCA-associated vasculitides (granulomatosis with polyangiitis, microscopic polyangiitis, eosinophilic granulomatosis) are pauci-immune. Direct immunofluorescence on renal biopsy shows little or no IgG, IgA, or complement deposits. The term is fundamental to classifying glomerulonephritis pathologically.<br><br>Lack of white blood cells (option A) is leukopenia, unrelated; resistance to steroids (option B) describes treatment response; total lack of immune system (option D) describes severe immunodeficiency, all distinct from the immunostaining pattern definition of pauci-immune.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Heerfordt’s syndrome (Uveoparotid fever) in Sarcoidosis includes all EXCEPT:',o:['High blood pressure','Uveitis','Facial nerve palsy','Parotid gland enlargement'],a:0,e:`High blood pressure is the exception in Heerfordt syndrome; uveoparotid fever consists of uveitis, parotid enlargement, facial nerve palsy, and fever, without hypertension.<br><br>Heerfordt syndrome (uveoparotid fever) is a specific subacute presentation of sarcoidosis. The four classical components define the syndrome. Treatment with corticosteroids addresses the granulomatous inflammation.<br><br>Uveitis (option B) is a defining component; facial nerve palsy (option C) is part of the syndrome; parotid enlargement (option D) is also part of the tetrad, leaving only high blood pressure (option A) outside the Heerfordt definition.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which medication is first-line for symptomatic Sarcoidosis?',o:['Azathioprine','Hydroxychloroquine','Methotrexate','Corticosteroids'],a:3,e:`Corticosteroids are first-line for symptomatic sarcoidosis; oral prednisolone reduces granulomatous inflammation and improves symptoms in pulmonary, cardiac, neurological, and ocular sarcoidosis.<br><br>Treatment is initiated for symptomatic disease, organ-threatening involvement, or hypercalcaemia. Steroid-sparing agents (methotrexate, azathioprine, hydroxychloroquine) are added in chronic disease. Asymptomatic Stage I disease often requires no treatment given high spontaneous remission rates.<br><br>Azathioprine (option A) is a steroid-sparing agent used after initial steroid response; hydroxychloroquine (option B) is used for skin and joint disease; methotrexate (option C) is used as steroid-sparing therapy, none being first-line as monotherapy.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with jaw claudication most likely has:',o:['Buerger’s disease','Dental caries','Giant cell (Temporal) arteritis','Sarcoidosis'],a:2,e:`A patient with jaw claudication most likely has giant cell (temporal) arteritis; pain on chewing reflects ischaemia of muscles of mastication from inflammation of facial branches.<br><br>Most commonly affects branches of carotid artery. Unilateral headache (temporal artery), jaw claudication. May lead to irreversible blindness due to ophthalmic artery occlusion. Associated with polymyalgia rheumatica.<br><br>Buerger disease (option A) affects distal extremities of young smokers; dental caries (option B) cause local tooth pain not muscle ischaemia on chewing; sarcoidosis (option D) does not cause jaw claudication, distinguishing GCA as the cause.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Takayasu’s arteritis, which imaging is preferred to visualize the vessel wall thickening?',o:['Ultrasound of the liver','MR Angiography (MRA) or CT Angiography (CTA)','Chest X-ray','Bone scan'],a:1,e:`MR angiography (MRA) or CT angiography (CTA) is preferred to visualise vessel wall thickening in Takayasu arteritis; both modalities show wall oedema and luminal narrowing.<br><br>MRI is preferred for repeated assessment in young patients due to absent radiation exposure. PET-CT identifies active inflammation. Conventional angiography is reserved for revascularisation planning. These modalities show vessel wall thickening characteristic.<br><br>Liver ultrasound (option A) is irrelevant to vessel walls; chest X-ray (option C) does not visualise vessel walls adequately; bone scan (option D) detects osseous metabolism not vascular inflammation, leaving MRA/CTA as preferred.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Why is smoking cessation mandatory in Buerger’s disease?',o:['Because continued tobacco use leads to inevitable disease progression and amputation','To prevent pneumonia','To lower blood pressure','To prevent lung cancer'],a:0,e:`Smoking cessation is mandatory in Buerger disease because continued tobacco use leads to disease progression and amputation; abstinence is the only intervention reliably halting progression.<br><br>Heavy smokers, males under 40 are typical patients. Even occasional tobacco exposure may trigger relapse. No pharmacological therapy substitutes for cessation. Bypass surgery and sympathectomy offer limited benefit since distal vessels are too small.<br><br>To prevent pneumonia (option B) is incidental benefit; to lower blood pressure (option C) is unrelated; to prevent lung cancer (option D) is also tangential, with disease-specific progression and amputation being the rationale.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with Wegener\'s has positive c-ANCA. What is the target antigen?',o:['Myeloperoxidase','Proteinase 3 (PR3)','Lactoferrin','Elastase'],a:1,e:`Proteinase 3 (PR3) is the target antigen of c-ANCA in Wegener granulomatosis; the cytoplasmic immunofluorescence pattern reflects autoantibodies against this neutrophil granule serine protease.<br><br>Triad of focal necrotising vasculitis, necrotising granulomas in lung and upper airway, and necrotising glomerulonephritis. PR3-ANCA/c-ANCA positivity supports diagnosis. Treat with cyclophosphamide and corticosteroids; rituximab is alternative induction agent in severe disease.<br><br>Myeloperoxidase (option A) is the target of p-ANCA in microscopic polyangiitis and Churg-Strauss; lactoferrin (option C) is rarely targeted; elastase (option D) is not the standard ANCA target, leaving PR3 as the c-ANCA antigen specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'What is the prognosis for Stage I Sarcoidosis (hilar lymphadenopathy only)?',o:['Leads to heart failure','Usually progresses to lung failure','Requires immediate chemotherapy','Excellent, with high rates of spontaneous remission'],a:3,e:`Stage I sarcoidosis (hilar lymphadenopathy only) has excellent prognosis with high rates of spontaneous remission; over 70 percent resolve without treatment within two years.<br><br>Sarcoidosis radiographic staging: Stage 0 normal, Stage I hilar adenopathy alone, Stage II hilar adenopathy with parenchymal infiltrates, Stage III parenchymal infiltrates alone, Stage IV pulmonary fibrosis. Spontaneous remission falls with stage.<br><br>Heart failure (option A) is rare in Stage I disease; lung failure (option B) characterises Stage IV; immediate chemotherapy (option C) is inappropriate since spontaneous remission is the rule, leaving the excellent prognosis correctly described.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Hypersensitivity vasculitis typically presents on which part of the body?',o:['Palms and soles only','Scalp and neck','Lower extremities (dependent areas)','Trunk only'],a:2,e:`Hypersensitivity vasculitis typically presents on the lower extremities (dependent areas); gravity-dependent venule pressure favours immune complex deposition in the legs and ankles particularly.<br><br>Drugs (NSAIDs, antibiotics) and infections are the most common triggers. Skin biopsy shows leukocytoclastic vasculitis. Withdrawal of the offending drug typically produces resolution within days to weeks. Severe cases may require corticosteroids.<br><br>Palms and soles only (option A) suggest secondary syphilis or hand-foot-mouth disease; scalp and neck (option B) are uncommon vasculitis sites; trunk only (option D) is also unusual, with dependent lower limbs being the classical distribution.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The "blindness" in Temporal Arteritis is caused by:',o:['Glaucoma','Anterior Ischemic Optic Neuropathy (AION)','Retinal vein occlusion','Corneal ulcers'],a:1,e:`Anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy (AION) causes blindness in temporal arteritis; ophthalmic artery occlusion produces sudden painless vision loss, often irreversible without prompt corticosteroids.<br><br>Treat with high-dose corticosteroids prior to temporal artery biopsy to prevent blindness. Bilateral involvement may follow within days if untreated. Fundoscopy in acute phase may show pale, swollen optic disc. Vision loss rarely improves.<br><br>Glaucoma (option A) is intraocular pressure elevation, distinct from ischaemic neuropathy; retinal vein occlusion (option C) produces a different fundoscopic pattern with haemorrhages; corneal ulcers (option D) cause anterior segment pain not optic nerve infarction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In Takayasu\'s, the "early" prepulseless phase is often:',o:['Identified by a skin rash','Asymptomatic','Non-specific (fever, malaise, weight loss)','Characterized by severe gangrene'],a:2,e:`Early prepulseless phase of Takayasu arteritis is often non-specific (fever, malaise, weight loss); systemic inflammation precedes pulse deficits and vascular bruits by months.<br><br>Diagnosis is often delayed because constitutional symptoms mimic other inflammatory or infectious conditions. ESR is elevated. Imaging with MR or CT angiography may show early vessel wall thickening before pulse deficits develop.<br><br>Skin rash (option A) is not the typical early presentation; asymptomatic course (option B) is uncommon since constitutional symptoms predominate; severe gangrene (option D) reflects late-stage tissue ischaemia, not the early systemic inflammatory phase.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Sarcoidosis can cause which type of arrhythmia if the heart is involved?',o:['Heart block or ventricular arrhythmias','Only sinus tachycardia','It never affects the heart','Atrial fibrillation only'],a:0,e:`Sarcoidosis can cause heart block or ventricular arrhythmias when the heart is involved; granulomatous infiltration of conduction tissue and myocardium produces bradyarrhythmias and ventricular ectopy.<br><br>Cardiac sarcoidosis may present with sudden cardiac death, complete heart block, ventricular tachycardia, or heart failure. MRI with gadolinium and PET-CT detect myocardial involvement. Treatment includes corticosteroids and may require pacemaker.<br><br>Sinus tachycardia only (option B) is non-specific and not characteristic; sarcoid never affects the heart (option C) is wrong; atrial fibrillation only (option D) understates the broad arrhythmia spectrum, including heart block and ventricular tachycardia.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Which clinical feature helps distinguish Wegener’s from Goodpasture syndrome?',o:['Goodpasture has positive ANCA','Wegener’s does not affect the lungs','Both are the same disease','Wegener’s has upper respiratory (sinus/ear) involvement'],a:3,e:`Wegener granulomatosis has upper respiratory (sinus/ear) involvement, distinguishing it from Goodpasture syndrome; nasal septal perforation, chronic sinusitis, otitis media, and saddle-nose deformity occur in Wegener.<br><br>Goodpasture is anti-glomerular basement membrane disease causing pulmonary haemorrhage and rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis without upper airway disease. Wegener is ANCA-associated granulomatous vasculitis. Both can present with haemoptysis and haematuria.<br><br>Goodpasture has positive ANCA (option A) is incorrect since Goodpasture is anti-GBM antibody disease; Wegener does not affect lungs (option B) is wrong; both are the same disease (option C) is incorrect, leaving upper airway involvement as discriminator.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`}
  ];
})();